<html>

<title>Legislative Hotline</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.gif"></center>

<p>

<center><h2>Hotline for Week of November 22-29</h2></center>

<p>

Welcome to the FRC information line.  This message is being 
updated on Friday November 22 and will continue to be updated 
periodically until the 105th Congress reconvenes in January.

<p>

Gary L. Bauer, President of Family Research Council, delivered 
a message this past week challenging the Republican Party today 
to find its voice on values and to redirect its economic policy 
toward working class and middle class families.  On Wednesday, 
November 20th, in front of an audience at the Heritage 
Foundation, Bauer warned that "the great danger facing America 
is not from barbarians at the gates, but the sickness of our 
own hearts."  He continued,  "What is at stake is whether this 
great experiment in ordered liberty under God can survive.  
That was the great issue that should have been central to the 
presidential election . . . The warning signs of the failure of 
the 1996 campaign were these from the beginning.  The 
Republican unelected party leadership was obsessed for the last 
four years with the mantra of 'big tent.'  A big tent for what?  
To  what end?  To change America how?  To improve the prospects 
for our families and children in what way?  We can mock Bill 
Clinton's bridge to the 21st century, but it at least signals 
ideas.  Big tent signals that when it comes to ideas we don't 
care enough to make a case for what we believe."

<p>

Bauer went on to reveal that "The key fact of the American 
economy is this:  It is getting harder, not easier, for working 
families to make ends meet.  Yet the elite of the Republican 
party often seem not to recognize the problem.  It isn't just a 
problem of slow economic growth.  The real problem is that the 
take-home pay of workers has fallen behind the growth of the 
economy.  They get to keep less and less of what they earn . . . 
We have created 10 million-plus new jobs, but only eight 
million more workers are now employed.  Every three workers are 
holding down four jobs."

<p>

"There is much to be done, from pro-family tax reform to placing 
entitlements on a sound footing," Bauer offered, "But, the goals 
of these efforts can be summarized in a single phrase:  we must 
be, we will be, for working families.  We must support families 
that 'work' in that they are able to support themselves with the 
fruits of their labor . . . For way too long now both political 
parties have been guided by political consultants, pollsters and 
focus group gurus who substitute media manipulation for a 
governing philosophy.  We need to look no further for the 
growing cynicism of the American people . . . You don't need 
[political consultants and pollsters] to tell you what you 
believe.  Appeal to the better angels of the American people 
and trust them to respond as they always have when they hear 
the truth."

<p>

Family Research Council will continue to fight for the truth 
for the American people.  And as the 105th Congress prepares to 
convene in January, FRC will continue to develop public policy 
initiatives and recommendations that seek to restore the 
vitality of American families in this great nation.  

<p>

Thank you for calling the FRC Legislative Hotline.  And from 
all of us in FRC's Government Relations, we wish you and your 
family a Happy Thanksgiving.

<p><center>

<h4>Return to <a href="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.html">this 
week's</a> Hotline</h4>

<p><img src="/townhall/FRC/images/redline.gif"><p>

<a href="/townhall/FRC/images/navstrp2.map">
<img src="/townhall/FRC/images/navstrp2.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
