<li>    Wolfgang Munchau, "Clinton's Team Split on Drugs," <I >The Times</I> (London), December 8, 1993. <P>
<li>    In an interview with MTV, for example, when asked whether he would "inhale" given the chance to "do it over again," Clinton merely provoked laughter: "Sure, if I could. I tried before." MTV interview, June 12, 1992.<p>
<li>    Hearing before the Senate Judiciary Committee, October 20, 1993.<p>
<li>    Office of National Drug Control Policy, <I>National Drug Control Strategy: Budget Summary</I>, February 1994.<P>
<li>    Prosecution figures are derived from the Executive Office of U.S. Attorneys (EOUSA) as well as the Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts (AO). The AO and EOUSA numbers differ because the two entities practice a different "leading charge" system; only the AO includes misdemeanor cases; and the AO includes cases brought by magistrate judges.<p>
<li>    H.G. Reza, "Drug Runners Arrested at Border Often Go Free; Smuggling: Crackdown Leads to More Seizures, but Jail Overcrowding and Clashing Priorities Force Suspects' Release," <I>The Los Angeles Times</I>, May 12, 1996, p 1.<p>
<li>    Robert C. Bonner, "Clinton's Flawed Drug-Smuggling Policy," <I>San Diego Union-Tribune</I>, June 4, 1996.<p>
<li>    In 1989 constant dollars, the interdiction budget declined from $1.73 billion in FY 1992 to $1.05 billion in FY 1996.<p>
<li>    Customs cocaine seizures fell from 35.4 metric tons (mt) in FY 1993 to 10.7 mt in FY 1994. Coast Guard cocaine seizures fell from 15.4 mt in FY 1993 to 4.4 mt in FY 1994.<p>
<li>    The "disruption rate" is the total amount of cocaine and marijuana that is seized, jettisoned, or "aborted" (returned to the source country as a result of interdiction or law enforcement presence). Data sheet from Joint Interagency Task Force-East, Key West, Florida, April 26, 1996. The daily disruption rate fell from 435.1 kgs/day in 1993 to 228.7 kgs/day in 1994, and still further to 158.1 kgs/day during the first 15 weeks of 1996.<p>
<li>    U.S. Department of Justice, Drug Enforcement Administration, and Abt Associates, <I>Average Price and Purity of Cocaine in the United States, Average Price and Purity of Heroin in the United States</I>, May 28, 1996.<p>
<li>    According to the Department of Justice, 3.04 million cultivated plants were eradicated in 1995 compared to 7.49 million eradicated in 1992.<p>
<li>    The Park Service drug control budget was cut from $11.1 million in FY 1992 to $8.7 million in FY 1996.<p>
<li>    Office of National Drug Control Policy, <I>Pulse Check: National Trends in Drug Abuse</I>, June 1996.<p>
<li>    For example, a 43 percent increase in cocaine prices in 1990 (the first such increase in five years) paralleled a 27 percent reduction in cocaine-related emergency room admissions and overdoses (the first such reduction in 12 years).<P>
<li>    Eugene Richards, <I>Cocaine True, Cocaine Blue</I> (Aperture).<p>
<li>    C. Peter Rydell and Susan S. Everingham, <I>Controlling Cocaine: Supply Versus Demand Programs</I> (Santa Monica, Cal.: RAND, 1994).<p>
<li>    According to the Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse at Columbia University, 12-to 17-year-olds who use marijuana are 85 times more likely to graduate to cocaine than those who abstain from marijuana.<p>
<li>    Ann Devroy, "About-Face; Clinton to Restore Staff He Cut from Anti-Drug Office," <I>The Washington Post</I>, March 6, 1996, p. A15.<p>
<li>    Memorandum from the President of the United States to the Secretary of State, <I>Certification of Major Narcotics Producing and Transit Countries, Statement of Explanation: Mexico</I>, March 1, 1996.<p>
<li>    Michael Isikoff, "Drug Director Urged to Hire Hill Aides; Memo Asked Director to 'Do Something' for Congressman Rangel," <I>The Washington Post</I>, August 19, 1993, p. A27.<p>
<li>    Sally Satel, "Yes, Drug Treatment Can Work," <I>City Journal</I>, Summer 1995.<p>
</ol><p>
