<head>
<title>Beltway, U.S.A.
 -Dec. 31, 1996
 - by Andy Ingram
</title>
<meta name="description" content="Beltway, U.S.A., A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America by Andrew Ingram">
<meta name="keywords" content="Beltway USA U.S.A. Moral Ethical Financial Andy Ingram Andrew 495 conservative Conservative editorial opinion Town Hall townhall TownHall">

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<img alt="Beltway, U.S.A." src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/beltwayusa.gif">
<br><i>A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America</i>
<p>


<h2>Giving Up Too Early</h2> 
<i>December 31, 1996</i>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<p>

"I give up, its over."  In today's fly by night world, that's all it takes to destroy one of the most important institutions in society, Marriage.
<P>
Isn't it time to repeal so-called "no fault divorce" laws that allow people to simply shed their marital commitment like a pair of dirty socks.  Over the past thirty years, no-fault divorce laws have been destroying marriage as an institution of life-long commitment.  Much like the debate over "same-sex" marriages, this is a debate over the definition of marriage.  Are we going to let marriage become simply a way of getting better health-care benefits and cheaper car insurance or are we going to elevate it as one of the most important institutions in our society.
<P>
This spring, Florida State Representative Steve Wise of Jacksonville will be introducing legislation to repeal Florida's twenty-five year old "no-fault divorce" law.  It will be a real battle as the liberal groups will try to scare the legislators into thinking the bill would legalize spouse-abuse or something.  On the contrary, it will stop the child abuse that results from a broken marriage.
<P>
When a man and a woman make a commitment to marriage, it is a commitment for life.   Adults get all the opportunities they want to date or meet different people but when two people decide to get married, they must understand what a significant and permanent step they are taking.  It is true that half of all marriages end in divorce, but this should not condemn us all.  Most people get married and stick it out through thick and thin.  The high rate of divorce results in large part because the same people are getting into multiple marriages and then ducking out several times.
<P>
A Florida women I talked with had four husbands since she was twenty and was now divorcing the fifth.   There were valid reasons for a couple of the break-ups but at least two of the marriages ended because they simple thought married like was too difficult.  The tragedy of this is that three children from three husbands were born.  She told me that all she had to do for the latest divorce was sign a simple form in one of those divorce chapels which work a lot like their counterparts in Las Vegas.
<P>
It is about time that we eliminate the term "irreconcilable differences" from divorce law.  All it really means is that the adults in question aren't mature enough to work it out.   Repealing the "no-fault" laws would mean that the person wanting the divorce would have to show cause such as desertion, abuse or infidelity.
<P>
Children are the biggest losers because of "no-fault" divorce.  1 out of 4 children live in a single parent home and a lot of these children could be saved by not letting there parents split up simply because they can't be bothered to go to counseling and work it out.  Anyone who's married will tell you that its not always a piece of cake.  You can't act like a selfish teenager anymore because you have to make sacrifices for the good of your new family.
<P>
We need to stop encouraging this trial-and-error attitude toward marriage and go back to where, as Bob Dole put it, "Your word is your bond."


<p>
God bless you in your efforts,<p>
<center>
<img alt="Andrew Ingram" src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/sig.gif">
<p>
<br>
