<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<img alt="Beltway, U.S.A." src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/beltwayusa.gif">
<br><i>A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America</i>
<p>


<h2>Democrats, Don't Kid Yourselves</h2> 
<i>December 23, 1996</i>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<p>
Democrats are celebrating this week because they believe that by getting the Speaker of the House to admit to a few improprieties, they are providing cover for their own problems with the illegal fundraising practices of the White House and the Democratic National Committee.  In a few months they will wake up with a hangover realizing that they were wrong.
<p>
For almost four years now, the truth about Whitewater has been slow getting out.  Republicans for the longest time, felt that this was their silver arrow that would bring down the president.  As we now know, it didnt, in large part because it is too complex for most of the American public to care about, let alone understand.  The Democrats should understand that the complex tax laws that the Speaker is accused of admitted to bending, have the same qualities that stop the average American from caring.
<p>
It is my opinion that the American people are not so much concerned about whether every last tax regulation was complied with, but rather whether our political process is being corrupted. The Speaker is only accused of being too partisan when he was not supposed to, and hiring a poor lawyer whom he didnt supervise enough. On the other hand, it is quickly becoming obvious that the DNC and the White House have systematically sold access to the Administration and political appointments to the highest bidder.  Only the prestige of the Presidency is saving Mr. Clinton.  If these revelations were coming out about a mayor or a city councilman, we would surely have heard the word "bribe" by now.  The big question concerning the political system is . . . . . . .   shouldnt campaign/legal defense fund donations which are rewarded with ambassadorship, committee appointments, and policy positions be called what they are, Bribes?
<p>
In this great democracy, we (the average American) believe that the government derives it power from us, and that we all have a theoretical part ownership in its institution.  I for one, do not appreciate my 1/275,000,000  share of the Lincoln bedroom being rented out to drug pushers, arms dealers, a foreign businessmen trying to alter American policy.
<p>
The president has tried to cover-up his troubles by clinging onto the Campaign Finance Reform bandwagon.  What he doesnt realize, it that we would be happy if he would just follow the laws that are on the books currently.
<p>
The current push for campaign finance reform is as misguided as the push just after the Nixon resignation.  The current system limits the amount of influence that the average American can have, giving all the power to wealthy Americans, corporations, and lobbyists.  That is as much as the liberals and I agree on.  The proper solution is not to limit spending more but to allow individuals to contribute more.   The fact that it costs a lot of money to run a house or senate race is not a problem.  This country is big and limiting spending will only limit the amount of information that is disseminated to average voters.  This would have the result of giving all the power to the inside the Beltway lobbyists.
<P>
If only there were stronger penalties for breaking the laws on the books, then maybe campaign laws would be taken seriously. Otherwise, the politicians will continue to recognize that it is easier to get elected and just pay the fine later.
<p>
Exploiting  the Gingrich story will not be enough to disguise the stench coming from the 1600 Pennsylvania Ave.  Trie, Huang, and all the rest of the fundraising dropouts are coming home to add to the smell.   
<P>
Anybody got a can of Lysol?

<p>
God bless you in your efforts,<p>
<center>
<img alt="Andrew Ingram" src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/sig.gif">
<p>
<br>
