<body>
<title>Gary Palmer -- America At A Crossroads</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
America At A Crossroads
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

	My dad said that the corn in this year's garden is the tallest 
and prettiest that he had seen in a long time.  My mom agreed. "This 
is probably the best garden we have ever had," she said.  So my wife 
and children and I drove up to help them gather the fruit of their 
labor.
<p>
	In my job with the Alabama Family Alliance I am constantly 
dealing with issues that are directly related to how people live and 
their values.  On the way back to Birmingham I kept thinking about how 
much things have changed since I was a boy, particularly people's 
values.  Sadly, in our present culture, most people do not have the 
same appreciation for a good crop of corn that my parents do, nor the 
work ethic that it represents.
<p>
	You see, growing good corn or a good garden takes a combination 
of things that are not as prevalent as they once were.  First of all, 
gardening takes a certain amount of optimism. Unfortunately, people 
today often lack the optimism that their labors will be rewarded in 
proportion to the effort they put forth.  Anyone who has ever grown 
corn knows that no matter how much work you put in preparing the 
ground, planting, fertilizing and hoeing, there is no guarantee of the 
quantity or quality of the harvest.  
<p>
	There is a prevailing cynicism that has taken root among many 
Americans that things are going downhill and getting worse every day.  
Some of that cynicism has been fueled by the growing welfare state.  
In the last 20 years there has been an explosion of illegitimacy 
subsidized by the government, or more accurately, by people who work 
and maintain legitimate families.  At the same time, entitlement 
spending for senior citizens, in a perverse sort of way, pits 
grandparents against their children and grandchildren who are having 
to pay more and more of their income to support the failing social 
security system and medicare.  
<p>
	America is quickly becoming a nation divided between two classes 
of people: those who work for a living and those who live off those 
who work.  It is as though the one who plants and works the garden 
must helplessly stand by and watch the government tramp through it, 
take forty percent or more of it and give it to people who do nothing.  
<p>
	But antagonism toward the welfare state is just part of the 
problem.  There is an overall anxiety about the future of the country.  
Politically, socially, academically and spiritually, it seems that all 
of our institutions are in decline and the most troubling thing of all 
is that many, if not most, people think that the decline is 
irreversible. 
<p>

	One of the amazing things about all this is that many of our 
problems are the result of the action, or inaction, of each of us.  
Take politics for example.  I am constantly being told by people how 
upset they are with the government or an individual politician.  
Inevitably they ask the question: What can I do?  My answer, which is 
often greeted with a blank look, is that they should be good citizens.
<p>
	Democracy is like my parent's garden.  If you want a good crop of 
corn or anything else you must work to get it.  If we expect our 
government to do the things it is supposed to do then we must be 
prepared to do our part.  If we want the government out of social 
welfare, then we as individuals and communities and religious 
institutions must be willing to take responsibility for caring for 
those who need our help.
<p>
	If we want lower taxes, then we must expect less from the 
government.  If we want better education, then we must get involved in 
our schools.  This is how democracy works.  It depends on the 
character, resourcefulness and cooperativeness of its people.  
Otherwise it will decline and give way to socialism or, even worse, 
despotism.
<p>
	Change, particularly the kind of political change that America 
really needs, will require a tremendous investment of effort and 
sacrifice.  If we are disgusted with the lack of character and honesty 
in our government, then people of strong moral values, who have the 
intelligence and ability and courage to do what is best for our 
country, will have to become involved at every level.  
<p>
	America is at a major social and historical crossroads.  Most of 
us have grown up thinking in terms of what the government should or 
will do for us.  But that mindset must change if we want to preserve 
democracy, and more fundamentally, our liberty.  There is a lot of 
hard work to be done, but I think it will be worth our effort.       
<p>
 -- <a href="mailto:alfamallia@aol.com">Gary Palmer</a>
<p>
<p>
<br>

