<body>
<title>Gary Palmer -- Paid "Volunteerism"?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Paid "Volunteerism"
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

	Based on the figures from the General Accounting Office (GAO) in 
Washington, D.C., the average blue-collar worker in Alabama would be 
better off to quit his or her present job and become a volunteer.  
<p>
	In case you don't know, AmeriCorps is President Clinton's idea 
for getting more people to do volunteer work.  The program is supposed 
to encourage a spirit of volunteerism especially among teenagers.  The 
problem is that all that volunteer spirit is being paid out of your 
pocket with your tax dollars.  
<p>
	When the program was introduced there were many claims made by 
the Clinton Administration and the Democrats who controlled Congress 
at the time the bill was passed.  For instance, it was claimed that 
the volunteers would be non-governmental.  But the fact is that out of 
the first 20,000 volunteers, 5,700 of them worked for federal or state 
government with the per volunteer costs ranging from $31,592 to 
$43,865, according to the GAO study.
<p>
	Under the president's AmeriCorps program, the average hourly cost 
per volunteer runs about $15.68.  That is over $26,000 per year for 
volunteer service.  A full-time volunteer gets $7,400 for 1,700 hours 
of "volunteer service," plus $9,400 toward payment of higher education 
debts over two years, and automatic health and child care benefits.  
The rest of the money is to cover the salaries of Washington 
bureaucrats who run the program.   	
<p>
	These same bureaucrats tell us that AmeriCorps operates with a 
very low overhead, about five percent.  The GAO audit, however, showed 
that over 50 percent of the average expense per volunteer was used to 
cover overhead and management expenses.
<p>
	It was also claimed that the AmeriCorps program would leverage 
private support with federal dollars.  But 93 percent of the funding 
comes from federal, state, and local taxpayers; only about $1,800 -- 
less than seven percent -- comes from private sources.
<p>
	AmeriCorps is also supposed to be non-partisan, but it has 
already established a record of liberal activism.  In one case 
protesters subsidized by an AmeriCorps grant prevented U.S. Speaker of 
the House Newt Gingrich from addressing the National Association of 
Counties.  Another AmeriCorps grant of $1.2 million was awarded to a 
community association in Denver which coerced AmeriCorps members into 
distributing campaign leaflets in a city council election.
<p>
	Another AmeriCorps grant that is drawing fire from the 
Republicans is a grant of $400,000 to the AFL-CIO to provide 
management training to people who receive AmeriCorps grants.  The 
problem with the grant to the AFL-CIO is that they have publicly 
stated that they intend to spend $35 million to oust the Republicans 
from Congress.  Plus, given the corruption that has ravaged organized 
labor over the years, you have to wonder what kind of management 
techniques the volunteers will be taught.
<p>
	From the perspective of many Republicans, this is nothing more 
than giving federal tax dollars to liberals who will use it against 
them.  And to add insult to injury, Eli Segal, campaign chief of staff 
for the 1992 Clinton/Gore campaign, has just been named the chairman 
of the board of the Corporation for National Service, which is over 
AmeriCorps. 
<p>
	The Clinton Administration is pushing Congress to keep AmeriCorps 
funded.  Congress is considering funding AmeriCorps at $365 million in 
1997 even though most of the Republican members of Congress know that 
the program is grossly inefficient and an extraordinary waste of 
taxpayer money.  But my guess is that since most of the Republicans 
have been pretty gutless on several issues this year, AmeriCorps will 
live to waste our money at least one more year.
<p>
	Perhaps the biggest problem with AmeriCorps is that paying people 
to volunteer undermines the civic spirit of pitching in and helping.  
Nearly 90 million Americans provide unpaid service each year, most of 
it through religious organizations.  The actual hours of volunteer 
service provided has actually increased by more than 50 percent since 
1981.  Yet the Clinton administration thinks that there are serious 
deficiencies in the voluntary sector that only another federal 
bureaucracy can fix.
<p>
	What many fear is that federally subsidized paid volunteers will 
cause real volunteer-based groups to become dependent on the federal 
government.  Given the federal government's track record, that would 
be a shame.  
<p>
 -- <a href="mailto:alfamallia@aol.com">Gary Palmer</a>
<p>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
