<html>
<body>
<title>David F. Nolan -- Bombs Bursting In Air?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
UNCONVENTIONAL WISDOM
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
Dole's Legacy
<br> by David F. Nolan
</i>
<p>
I live in Orange County, California, about 75 miles north of San 
Diego, where the GOP hierarchy (and much of the midarchy and 
lowerarchy, as well) will meet next week to confirm the selection of 
Bob Dole as their presidential nominee. Orange County is one of the 
most Republican places on Earth. It  routinely supplies the GOP margin 
of victory in California, and our U.S. Representatives include Dana 
Rohrabacher and Christopher Cox, two of the most conservative men in 
Congress.
<p>
And nobody I have spoken with in the last two months expects Bob Dole 
to win the presidency. The question on people's minds is not "will 
Dole lose?" but rather "how badly will he lose?" and more 
specifically, whether the impending train wreck will cost the GOP its 
majority in the House of Representatives. 
<p>
In public, you will hear much lip-service to the idea that Dole can 
turn things around, close the gap, etc.--but in private, nobody 
believes it. Dole has no discernible vision and stirs no passions. 
Republican members of Congress, eager to desert a sinking ship, have 
collaborated with Clinton on welfare reform, health care, and other 
matters, leaving Dole out in the cold. This gives the ex-Senator from 
Kansas only one real meaningful role to play in the next three months, 
but it is an important one.  By his choice of running-mate and 
campaign issues, Dole will play a major role in defining the 
Republican party as the U.S. heads into the 21st century.
<p>
For, as the 1996 primaries clearly showed, the GOP has yet to settle a 
fundamental division within its ranks.  One wing of the party, 
typified by Steve Forbes, is driven primarily by a desire to cut taxes 
and regulations--to make government "go away" and let an unfettered 
marketplace provide prosperity. They tend to be "moderate" (but not 
liberal) on social issues. The other wing, represented by Pat 
Buchanan, is the mirror image of the Forbes camp: socially 
conservative, strongly opposed to abortion, suspicious of free trade.
<p>
Dole would like to paper over this schism, at least until Election 
Day.  His unsuccessful attempt to introduce "tolerance" language into 
the party's abortion plank is a perfect example of Dole-style 
pragmatism: negotiating, deal-making, trying to find the middle 
ground.  Unfortunately for Dole, the hard-line social conservatives 
are having none of it. They figure Dole is going to lose anyhow, and 
they care more about the abortion plank than they do about the 
candidate.
<p>
This puts Dole in an interesting position. Every survey I have seen 
indicates that most Americans are somewhere "in the middle" on the 
abortion issue--favoring safe and legal abortion during the early 
months of a pregnancy, and becoming progressively less sympathetic to 
the idea in later months. A great majority have no problem with the 
idea of a "morning after" pill; an even larger majority oppose 
"partial birth" abortions. However, the two largest political parties 
are each dominated by a vocal minority: the GOP by militant pro-
lifers, the Democrats by militant pro-choicers. 
<p>
Dole cannot win the election with hard-line pro-life voters alone. 
Indeed, as noted earlier, he probably can't win at all. But if he is 
to have even a long-shot chance, he needs the Forbes-style 
conservatives.  And his best bet in this regard is to select a 
running-mate who typifies the fiscally conservative, socially moderate 
wing of the party: Christine Todd Whitman. 
<p>
Whitman, currently the nation's only woman governor, is a Forbes 
protege with a strong record of tax-cutting; the non-partisan Cato 
Institute recently ranked her the 5th-best governor in this regard. 
She is pro-choice, but not militant about it, and is Dole's best--
perhaps only--hope of closing the "gender gap" in the voting booth. 
And regardless of whether Dole wins or loses, by choosing Whitman as 
his running mate he will show that his talk of tolerance and openness 
is more than rhetoric. 
<p>
It should be an interesting convention.
<p>
DFN
<p>
<center>
--------------------------------------------------------------
</center>
<br>
<i>
UNCONVENTIONAL WISDOM is a column of commentary and opinion by David 
F. Nolan, a self-described "radical Constitutionalist" who first 
became politically active during the Goldwater campaign. In the 
intervening years, Mr. Nolan has worked with the Young Americans for 
Freedom, the Liberty Amendment Committee, the Libertarian Party and 
the International Society for Individual Liberty. He presently makes 
his home in Orange County, California. He may be reached by <a href="mailto:73303.1612@CompuServe.com">e-mail</a>.
</i>
<p><p>


