<Title>Biographical Information on Clifford D. May</Title>

<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote>
<blockquote>
<center><h2>Biographical Information on<br>Clifford D. May</h2></center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>
Clifford D. May is the Associate Editor of the Rocky Mountain News in Denver, Colorado.
<p>
Since joining the Rocky Mountain News in December of 1989. Mr. May has also written a weekly column for the paper. The column is distributed to newspapers nationwide through the Scripps Howard News Service.
<p>
Before moving to Colorado, Mr. May spent nearly a decade with the New York Times working as a general editor of the Sunday Magazine, metropolitan New York reporter, Washington correspondent, Africa correspondent and chief of the West Africa bureau, which he established for the Times in Abidjan, the Ivory Coast. For the Times, Mr. May covered events in more than a dozen African countries.
<p>
Earlier in his career, Mr. May was Senior Editor of the American edition of Geo magazine, a publication similar to National Geographic with a strong focus on environmental concerns around the world.
<p>
In the late 1970s, Mr. May was the Roving Foreign Correspondent for Hearst newspapers, reporting from Mexico, the Soviet Union, Northern Ireland, Iran and other nations. Hearst newspapers then included the San Francisco Examiner, the Boston Herald-American, the Baltimore News-American, the San Antonio Light and the Los Angeles Herald-Examiner.
<p>
During that same period, Mr. May also served as a special correspondent for CBS Radio News and for Bill Moyers' Journal/International Report at PBS.
<p>
For two and a half years beginning in 1975, Mr. May was an Associate Editor at Newsweek, specializing in international news.
<p>
Mr. May was a Contributing Editor of World Press Review Magazine. His freelance writing has appeared in the Atlantic Monthly, Forbes (including articles from China, Japan and Pakistan), Outside and other national publications. He has appeared on such national television shows as "The MacNeil/Lehrer News Hour," "This Week With David Brinkley" and "West 57th Street" and "Newstalk America."
<p>
He is the producer and moderator of "Roundtable," a weekly public affairs program broadcast on KRMA, Channel 6, the Rocky Mountain region's largest public television station. And from Sept. 1995 to Nov. 1996 he is serving as host of "Race for the Presidency," a nationally distributed, weekly, hour long program from TCI, the nation's largest cable television operator.
<p>
He also has a weekly talk show on NewsRadio 85 KOA, the most highly rated radio station in the Rocky Mountain region.
<p>
Mr. May holds two masters degrees from Columbia University, one from the School of Journalism (1975), the other from the School of International Affairs (1975). He was a candidate at Columbia's Russian Institute. He holds a certificate in Russian Language and Literature from the University of Leningrad (1972); his B.A. is from Sarah Lawrence College (1973) in Bronxville, NY.

<p>
<br>
<p>
<center>
 <a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
