http://www.cpac.org:80/townhall/columnists/otb/CO/may0728.html 204.71.237.74 19970108130321 text/html 4965
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 13:03:36 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 13-Aug-96 17:32:26 GMT
Content-length: 4778
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body>
<title>Clifford D. May --  What Molly Ivins Doesnt Know Could Fill A Newspaper</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<h3>
 What Molly Ivins Doesnt Know Could Fill A Newspaper
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>
<i>by Clifford D. May</i>
<p>
 July 28, 1996
<p>
If a Washington pundit were to let it slip that he thought the secretary of 
energy was the aide who supplied Bill Clinton with Snickers bars hed be 
a laughingstock.
<p>
Were a culture critic to mention that she thought Hamlet was a village in 
Denmark, it would ruin her career.
<p>
But let an award-winning, nationally syndicated columnist display the 
most astonishing ignorance of basic economics and it passes without 
notice.
<p>
What prompts these observations is a recent column by Molly Ivins, an 
engaging writer and probably a delightful dinner companion to boot. But 
Ivins is, to put it gently, an economic illiterate.
<p>
The number of misconceptions littering the column in front of me is 
simply staggering. I have space to talk about only a few:
<ol>
<li><i>. . . 51 million Americans own stock either individually or through 
their pension plans . . . that leaves four-fifths or us -- thats 80% for you 
number-lovers -- who dont have a stake in the fortunes of Wall Street.
</i><p>
Molly, had you checked with Dow Jones, youd have learned that 160 
million Americans own stocks either directly or through funds and 
pensions. Thats well over half of Americans who have a stake in Wall 
Street.
<p>
<li><i>Investors -- who used to be called by their proper name, 
speculators -- do not help build bridges, produce widgets or care for 
children. Theyve never dry-cleaned a suit, served a meal or made a 
shovel.</i>
<p>
Investors most emphatically do help build bridges, produce widgets and 
care for children because all these activities depend on investments of -- 
dare I say the word? -- capital. And who, pray tell, will invest that capital 
if not investors?
<p>
Also, Molly, investors and speculators are not the same thing. But rather 
than try to explain the difference (or argue why even speculators are 
useful), let me just point out that, like them, you and I earn our livings 
producing things less tangible than shovels and dry-cleaned suits. So 
what?
<p>
<li><i>When Bill Clinton came in 1992, he wanted to spend money on the 
infrastructure, provide jobs, boost the economy.</i>
<p>
But, good golly, Miss Molly, thats exactly what those villainous 
investors do! Are you saying that instead of having investors voluntarily 
invest their money, youd prefer that the IRS confiscate more of the 
money people earn and turn it over to government bureaucrats to 
disburse? And why do you think its jim-dandy when the government 
provides jobs at the helium reserve but a crying shame when corporations 
employ workers producing things consumers actually want?
<p>
<li><i>Bond traders -- now theres a collections of parasites. Ill take a 
welfare mother over a bond trader in terms of productive contributions to 
society any day. And twice on Sunday.</i>
<p>
Whoa, Molly! What business do you think bond traders are in? Bondage? 
Bond traders are in the money-lending business. You do exactly what 
they do whenever you deposit your pay check in a local bank. The bank 
then lends your money (to people who want to buy homes, for instance) 
and share the interest paid on those loans with you.
<p>
In fact, unless youre giving your income away to Bubba and Bubbette 
you must be a lender, and investor or a more conspicuous consumer than 
even Chip and Binkie. Or do you stash your cash in a mattress?
<p>
More to the point, lending money is not just a productive contribution to 
society - its indispensable.
<p>
<li><i>Its not people gettin rich without effort that chaffs me; its how 
dumb they are. Mergers and acquisitions, leveraged buyouts and their 
effect on the economy and on human beings. DONT GET ME 
STAAAAARTED.</i>
<p>
No doubt some people get rich without effort. You, for example, are 
doing very nicely without having mastered Economics 101. If you had, 
youd know that the effect of mergers, acquisitions and leveraged 
buyouts is precisely to keep managers from sleepin in the shade.
<p>
But then there is so much you fail to grasp about how wealth is created 
and poverty alleviated. If youre ever to understand such things. Molly, 
YOU BETTER GET STAAAAARTED!
<p>
</ol>
</blockquote></blockquote>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</body>
</html>
