<body>
<title>Phil Brennan -- Guilty - With An Explanation</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Guilty - With An Explanation
 </h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
By Phil Brennan, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.pacg.com/pvbr/">Wednesday On The Web</a>
</i>
<p>
A lot of people in the media and the present administration are 
getting all riled up over  the religious right, a menace apparently 
more dangerous than smoking tobacco, eating fatty foods or having 
unprotected sex.
<p>
The demons of the religious right, they warn, are guilty of wanting to 
take away your freedom and therefor must be dealt with quickly, before 
they destroy America and put everybody in concentration camps.
<p>
All this scares me silly, because I'm guilty of being a full-fledged 
member of the religious right, and I do not want to be dealt with, 
especially by members of the pagan left.
<p>
So, in admitting guilt, I plead nolo contendere with a mitigating 
explanation, to wit: I simply couldn't help myself.. I was an abused 
child!
<p>
I was psychologically abused by my parents, by the Sisters of St. 
Joseph, by the Jesuits and by the United States Marine Corps.
<p>
My parents, for example, forced upon me the blatantly sexist notion 
that women are different from men in a multitude of ways and deserve 
to be placed on pedestals and paid homage to by virtue of their 
natural and often sacrificial roles as wives and mothers.
<p>
 They taught me such clearly anti-feminist practices as tipping my hat 
when encountering a member of the opposite sex, or standing when a 
woman entered the room or got up from a table. They taught me to 
revere women, and treat them with admiration and tenderness.
<p>
Moreover, my parents twisted my psyche by demanding absolute - and 
totally undemocratic - obedience to their every command. They even 
insisted that I treat all adults as superiors who were to be given the 
utmost respect whether I liked them or not. 
<p>
By raising me as a Christian and making me fulfill my religious duties 
they doomed me to a life filled with taboos that keep me from giving 
full rein to all those alluring animal passions society sees as 
necessary to mental health, thus insuring that I'll be tortured by 
guilt if I give into them, and emotionally warped if I don't. 
<p>
And if I'm guilty of bigotry because I insist that homosexuality is 
unnatural, blame my mother and father, both of whom subscribed to the 
centuries-old  Judeo-Christian belief that single-sex coupling is 
unnatural and immoral and that those who engage in it outrage decency.   
<p>
They taught me prejudice by telling me that there are good people and 
bad people. And based on the theory that if you lie down with hounds 
you'll come up with fleas, they taught me to avoid having any truck 
with the bad ones if I don't want to spend all my time scratching flea 
bites.
<p>
The nuns corrupted me with such illiberal ideas as the existence of  
heaven and hell,  that God holds people responsible for their actions, 
and that good people go to heaven and bad ones go to hell.
<p>
The nuns also scarred my psyche by insisting that the Ten Commandments 
are really commandments, and not just quaint suggestions to be 
followed or ignored, depending upon my personal ideas of what's right 
and what's wrong.
<p>
The Jesuits abused me psychologically be making me study the history 
of Western Christian civilization, an obviously racist subject 
infested with nothing but dead white European males, an odious breed 
according to the pagan elite. 
<p>
The Jesuits even had the gall to hold up as objects of admiration such 
historic figures as Ludwig von Beethoven, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, 
Leonardo Da Vinci, St. Francis of Assisi and St. Thomas Aquinas, 
despite the fact that they're all dead, all white, all European, all 
males, and all of them therefor utterly unworthy of respect.
<p>
The Jesuits also drummed into my head the socially-inappropriate 
concept  that government is, in the words of Thomas Jefferson: "A 
fearful master."  They further alienated me from big brother by 
repeating Dorothy Parker's admonition that the power to do things for 
you is the power to do things to you. 
<p>
Finally, I was abused by my chauvinistic Marine Corps superiors who 
failed to develop my sensitivity, or to raise my consciousness, or to 
make me into this woebegone era's concept of what a real man should 
be: a quivering tower of jelly.
<p>
Clearly, I can't be held responsible for my political orientation. 
It's not my fault. I was abused.
<p>
The child within me suffers from attention-surplus disorder.
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
