<body>
<title>Phil Brennan -- I Do Not Envy Kenneth Starr</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
I Do Not Envy Kenneth Starr
 </h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
By Phil Brennan, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.pacg.com/pvbr/">Wednesday On The Web</a>
</i>
<p>
I do not envy Kenneth Starr.
<p>
As the man charged with getting to the bottom of Whitewater and related
high crimes and misdemeanors, Starr is facing some tough -- and to him,
perilous choices.
<p>
It has been said that Starr is hypersensitive to the fact that indicting
either of the Clintons or their closest White House associates so close to
the presidential elections would obviously have a major effect on the
outcome of the race. And that he is, therefor, understandably reluctant to
do so.
<p>
He knows, of course, that no matter how solid a case he might have against
his targets, the media elite and Clinton's other allies will savage him in
a manner far worse than they did before he got his convictions against Jim
Guy Tucker and the MacDougals. They'll bellow that the indictments are
politically motivated -- the act of a Republican extremist (to the media
and the White House, all Republicans are, of course, extremists ) using
unfair means to defeat an innocent democrat president -- and as such are an
outrage against all that is good and decent.
<p>
Can't you just hear obnoxious little George Stephanopoulos sniveling about
the terrible injustice of it all. Or Dan Rather (who never fails to
identify Ken Starr as "the Republican special counsel,") going ballistic on
national TV.
<p>
There would, in fact, be a media firestorm unmatched even by the
conflagration that surrounded Nixon during his final days in the White
House. And it would be aimed at trying to provoke a backlash against the
GOP by making a victim out of poor Bill Clinton.
<p>
And the facts in the case would be ignored -- or blythely denied a la Bill
Clinton (who isn't named Blythe for nothing).
<p>
So it wouldn't be all that difficult to excuse Starr if he held back on
indicting either of the Clintons or any major administration figure ....
except that to do so would be to not only postpone the inevitable thrashing
he'll get from the Clintonites, but would also create a governmental crisis
that would make the "long national nightmare" that Jerry Ford called the
Watergate affair look like a romp through the Garden of Eden.
<p>
Those close to the Washington end of Starr's investigation bluntly describe
Hillary's sworn testimony as littered with examples of outright perjury,
and they say they have the goods to prove it. Moreover, it is said that
those goods have been displayed to a grand jury alleged to be on the verge
of voting true bills against the First Lady and some of her associates.
<p>
Meanwhile, down in Arkansas, it is said that Clinton's erstwhile partner
James MacDougal (the man he called "MacDollar" in recognition of
MacDougal's storied beneficence on his behalf ) is singing his head off to
Starr's people -- and he has a lot to sing about ... a veritable funeral
dirge -- he knows, after all, where all the bodies are buried.
<p>
He was, for example, the third man in the room when then-governor Clinton
allegedly put the arm on David Hale to get that $300,000 SBA loan for
MacDougal -- a charge that Clinton has publically called "a bunch of bull,"
and denied under oath during his testimony in the Tucker-MacDougal trial.
<p>
So it comes down to this: If Starr postpones indictments until after the
election even though fully justified by the evidence, he will deprive his
fellow Americans of vitally important knowledge they need to make an
informed choice in the elections.
<p>
If that evidence is strong enough to bring indictments against either of
the Clintons or their cohorts now, it will be strong enough to bring
Clinton down if he is re-elected. And the nation will face their worst
crisis since the Civil War.
<p>
The people need to be told now if there is even the slightest chance that
after the elections, they might well have a president or a first lady
facing months or even years of criminal proceedings and, possibly, prison
terms. To deny them that knowledge before they vote would be ... well ...
it would be a crime!
<p>
As I said, I do not envy Kenneth Starr.
<p>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
