<body>
<title>Richard Lessner -- Does Dole Have What It Takes?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>Does Dole Have What It Takes? Veepstakes Long Shot Thinks So
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

<i>By RICHARD LESSNER
<br>The Union Leader</i>
<p>
CAN BOB DOLE BEAT BILL CLINTON?
<p>
The answer to that question seems slightly less obvious today than it 
did a week ago -- but only slightly -- thanks to Mr. Dole's decision 
to bound over to the supply side and propose Reaganesque tax tats. For 
the first time, Mr. Dole has Bill Clinton on the defensive. Can he 
keep him there?
<p>
"If in October we're talking about tax cuts and the size of 
government. we win," says Gov. Steve Merrill, the Dole campaign's 
national chairman and a Veepstakes long shot (though our Granite State 
governor matches up pretty well with his description of the kind of 
running mate Mr. Dole is likely to pick).
<p>
I asked Gov. Merrill to drop by The Union Leader before he left for 
San Diego so we could chat about the Dole campaign. He was more 
generous with his time than he had to be in view of how roughly I've 
handled Mr. Dole.
<p>
"Okay, convince me." I said. "Relieve my conservative Angst. Tell me 
how Bob Dole is going to beat Clinton."
<p>
"Here's the thing that scares me the most," the governor began. "The 
American people have concluded that Bill Clinton is not trustworthy, 
but they'll vote for him; they think Dole is trustworthy, but they 
won't vote for him."
<p>
In other words, the character issue is a dud.
<p>
"The people know who Clinton is and they don't care. I keep telling 
the campaign it doesn't need any more negative campaigning on the 
character issue and they should drop it."
<p>
Gov. Merrill says that Bob Dole needs a positive message to bring home 
conservative voters. Right now, Bill Clinton is "renting" a lot of 
votes that properly should go to the Republican. About 25 percent Of 
those who identify themselves as "conservative" are thinking about 
voting for Bill Clinton.
<p>
"Clinton's ability to move to the popular ground is amazing!" Gov. 
Merrill lamented. "He's out there running against whoever it is that's 
been President these last four years "
<p>
Okay, so Bill Clinton is a political chameleon and Bob Dole cannot 
match his cloying folksiness. Mr. Dole is hardly the most telegenic 
candidate ever, the governor admits. He suggests that Republicans 
might want to do something other than watch TV on the nights of the 
Presidential debates.
<p>
"Bob Dole isn't as glib as Bill Clinton, the media's darling. But 
Clinton cannot match Bob Vole in sincerity." The voters will make a 
decision based on character, not image, Gov. Merrill insisted, though 
I was certain he had earlier suggested the character issue was a non-
starter.
<p>
Is this what Gov. Merrill fears the most in the campaign ahead, a Dole 
meltdown in the debates?
<p>
"No, we'll be okay there. What worries me the most is an inadvertent 
blunder that the press will jump all over. You know, they won't cut 
Dole any slack. None at all."
<p>
So why, I wanted to know, had the campaign been such a disaster on 
wheels prior to the big tax-cut announcement?
<p>
Well, Bob Dole has a hard time "staying on message." Gov. Merrill 
admits. He's had difficulty driving home his core message and has 
managed to get himself detoured into peripheral issues.
<p>
Part of the problem has been procedural, the governor insists. Sen. 
Dole wrapped up the nomination at an historically early date and the 
bruising primary fight left him wounded, broke and appearing weak.
<p>
"This has allowed Clinton to characterize Dole's issues. They've spent 
$11 million on TV ads backed up by the AFL/CIO's spending and we've 
been unable to respond." So, Sen. Dole has appeared issue-less because 
the campaign has been reluctant to stake out positions for the 
Clintonoids to trash.
<p>
Maybe the Doles should have gone on an extended vacation after the 
primaries, I suggested, holed-up somewhere out of sight and mind until 
the convention, thereby depriving Butt Man of a target.
<p>
Does the ghost of '92 haunt the Dole campaign, I asked? Is Team Dole 
traumatized by the conventional media wisdom that Pat Buchanan's 
Houston speech, George Bush's pro-life stand and alleged "extremism" 
cost Republicans the White House?
<p>
"No. Bush lost because he reversed himself on taxes and because the 
voters didn't believe the Republican Party really stood for what it 
said it did."
<p>
So, if it really is the economy, stupid, and not the social issues, 
why has Bob Dole seemingly gone out of his way to alienate the 
conservatives in the party on abortion, gun control, affirmative 
action?
<p>
This question gave Gov. Merrill some difficulty. He talked about Bob 
Dole's pro-life record and how it's important for the Dole campaign to 
bring together the party's fiscal and social conservatives -- the 
GOP's "head" and "heart," as the governor put it.
<p>
Does Bob Dull have the passion for the job, the necessary fire in the 
belly?
<p>
"Bob Dole knows he has to bring the party together and he will do it 
at the convention. This is not a Quixotic journey for him, nor an 
intellectual exercise. He wants this, He really wants to be President. 
He said to me once, 'Steve, do you realize this is the first 
generation of Americans that does not believe the future will be 
better than the past? I want to change that.' I know it doesn't always 
come across because Bob Dole isn't a very emotional guy in public, but 
he really believes this."
<p>
So, after almost 90 minutes, did Steve Merrill close the deal and 
persuade me that Bob Dole can beat Bill Clinton? Well, our ebullient 
governor is a cagey salesman and I hope I'm wrong, but there's an 
eerie sense of whistling past the graveyard in all of this.
<p>
 -- Richard Lessner
<p>
<p>
<br>

