<title>Richard Lessner -- White House Dopes: Apology? Don't Hold Your Breath, Newt</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
White House Dopes: Apology? Don't Hold Your Breath, Newt
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

Leon Panetta, chief of staff to our Presidential non-inhaler, owes 
Newt Gingrich an apology.
<p>
To refresh your memory, the incoming Speaker of the House got into hot 
water with Mr. Panetta back in December, 1994 when he revealed that a 
number of Clinton White House staffers were using illegal drugs when 
they were hired.
<p>
"Absolutey false," sputtered Mr. Panetta, "reckless accusations that 
impugn people's integrity." The non-inhaler's mouthpiece went on to 
lecture Mr. Gingrich on the proper comportment for a House Speaker.
<p>
Okay, fast forward to the present. Last month it was confirmed that 
what Mr. Panetta said was "absolutely false" was absolutely true: A 
dozen White House employees were unable to pass Secret Service and FBI 
security checks because of recent or current use of marijuana, crack 
cocaine and hallucinogens.
<p>
Now, a gentleman would apologize to Mr. Gingrich for, in effect, 
calling him a liar. And he would do so as publicly as he issued the 
insult. Has Mr. Panetta apologized? No. Will he? Probably not. Is he a 
gentleman? You be the judge.
<p>
Given the White House's cavalier attitude toward drugs - let alone the 
truth - is it any wonder that under the non-inhaler the war on drugs 
hasn't amounted to a skirmish? Teenage marijuana use has doubled since 
the non-inhaler took office, interdiction efforts have been gutted and 
the two Clinton drug czars have been all but invisible (quick, can you 
name the present generalissimo?)
<p>
While the White House postures over kids smoking cigarettes and 
dispatches a goofy "Butt Man" to heckle Bob Dole, the Clintonoids seem 
unperturbed by rising narcotic use among America's young people.
<p>
Indeed, former FBI agent Gary Aldrich, in his best-selling book 
"Unlimited Access," reports the Clinton dopers boasted of their drug 
use. Hillary Clinton called these and other Aldrich revelations 
"politically inspired fabrications." Apparently the first lady is 
taking lessons from Mr. Panetta.
<p>
 -- Richard Lessner
<p>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
</html>
