<body>
<title>TWA 800:  Has the 'Nation of Terror' Struck Again?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
TWA 800:  Has the 'Nation of Terror' Struck Again?
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

We take no satisfaction in having warned as recently as last Tuesday 
that the 'Nation of Terror' will continue to murder Americans until 
Washington begins to take stern measures against that archipelago of 
terrorist training bases, safe havens and patron governments that 
shield these jackals.
<p>
Was TWA 800 brought down by a terrorist bomb? This seems the most 
plausible explanation for the catastrophic destruction of the Boeing 
747, the Queen of the Skies, one of the safest aircraft in the world. 
Apart from an unprecedented major structural failure, an explosive 
device would be the suspected culprit. That the aircraft had arrived 
at New York's JFK Airport from Athens, one of the least secure 
airports in the world, is highly suggestive. The State Department 
recently issued an alert on the lax security at the Athens airport.
<p>
How many more? How many more Americans will have to die before the 
government of this country begins to put the lives of its citizens 
ahead of weasling considerations for foreign relations?
<p>
The bombers of Pan Am 103, who murdered 269 over Lockerbie, Scotland, 
reside in luxury in Libya, shielded by Moammar Gadhafy. Yet for all 
its bluff, bluster and brave talk, Washington has done nothing to 
bring the perpetrators to justice. Why? Our European "allies" do not 
want their lucrative commercial relations with oil-rich Libya 
disturbed by economic sanctions or trade embargoes. It also is known 
that the Libyan bombers were hired by Iran, the Pan Am atrocity a 
cold-blooded act of revenge for the accidental downing of an Iranian 
Airbus by the USS Vincennes. Has Iran been held accountable? Hardly.
<p>
The pathetic story of the Pan Am killers has been repeated many times 
over -- the Beirut Marine barracks and embassy bombings, the 
destruction of a French DC-10 in Africa, the recent bombings in Saudi 
Arabia, the North Korean bombing of a South Korean airliner, the 
murder of a U.S. Navy officer aboard hijacked TWA 840.
<p>
Terrorists always will have an advantage in open, democratic 
societies, and there never will be a perfect defense against such 
evil-doers. Yet the cowardly, craven inaction of the U.S. government 
on the slaughter of its citizens verges on the traitorous. Government 
has no greater purpose than to secure the physical safety of its 
citizens. In this, our government has failed, under both Republican 
and Democratic administrations.
<p>
 -- Richard Lessner
<p>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
