<title>The Hearthstone Press: A Biblical View Of Welfare</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>A Biblical View Of Welfare
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>
<i>
 by Rev. Howard Holtje
</i>
<p>

When someone stands up to say that the Welfare Program in this country 
is in trouble and in need for change people become very nervous 
thinking that those who truly are in need of assistance will be cut 
off (e.g. the elderly).  Many people would rather keep things as they 
are because they fear that those who are truly in need will be left 
destitute.  But, the fact is that many many people are abusing the 
system (i.e. receiving funds when they do not fit the criteria), it 
puts great strain on government resources and it is unbiblical.
<p>
The answer to the Welfare problem is found in the Bible.  In the New 
Testament book of 1 Timothy the Apostle Paul is instructing a young 
pastor whose name is Timothy about taking care of the elderly widows 
in his church.  The principles found in 1 Timothy 5:3-16 is the answer 
for the Welfare problem in the United States.  This answer was 
introduced in the political arena by President Reagan.
<p>
First, God does not put the responsibility of caring for the elderly 
and disadvantaged on the government.  It is unbiblical if that is 
where the responsibility lies.  The responsibility lies in the family.  
This is seen in 1 Timothy 5:4, "But, if any widow (anyone in need) 
have children or grandchildren, let them LEARN first, to show piety 
(real faith) at home and requite (repay) their parents; for that is 
good and acceptable before God."  This means that if you have elderly 
parent(s) it is not the responsibility of the government or nursing 
home (unless absolutely necessary).  It is your responsibility to care 
for their physical and emotional needs.
<p>
Unfortunately, many feel that their needy relative will be an 
inconvenience and "Hey, I have my own family to care for and my own 
life to live!"  But, didn't your parents sacrifice many of their wants 
for many years so that you can be who you are today?  This is why God 
tells us that if we care for our family (parents and grandparents 
included) we show that we are truly people who trust in Jesus ("Pure 
religion and undefiled before God the father is this: to help the 
fatherless and widows in their affliction." James 1:27) and in effect 
we are repaying our parents for all that they have done for us.  If 
they were not the best of parents we are still to care for them when 
they are elderly and in need.  It is hard to do but it is something we 
may need to LEARN.
<p>
Note what the Lord tells us in 5:8 concerning those who do not care 
for their parents/grandparents themselves.  "But if any provide not 
for his own and especially those of his own house, he has denied the 
faith and is worse than an infidel."
<p>
If there is no family or the family refuses to fulfill their God given 
responsibility, then the church must meet the needs of the elderly and 
others in need.  First, just as the family must LEARN to care for a 
parent so must the church LEARN to care for people long term.  I have 
observed that many many churches help people short term.  Meaning if 
there is a crises they are there.  But, if the crises does not go away 
and the need lingers on the people from the church dwindle away 
because this person is too much of a burden, "Hey, I have my own 
family to care for."  The church must hang in there for the long haul 
if it wants to be in God's will.
<p>
The church must do an investigation to determine whether or not the 
person is truly in need.  There are people who go from town to town 
going to church to church looking for hand-outs.  This is not the kind 
of person being addressed in 1 Timothy 5.  If the person fits the 
requirements of this passage the church becomes responsible for their 
well being physically and emotionally.
<p>
The above program is more difficult for you and me but the need of the 
people will be better met and the responsibility is properly placed 
first on the family and second on the church and NOT ON THE 
GOVERNMENT.

<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
