<body>
<title>The Hearthstone Press: Fox And McHale Both Vote For Welfare Reform</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Fox And McHale Both Vote For Welfare Reform
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

WASHINGTON - Both Congressman Jon Fox (R-13) and Congressman Paul 
McHale, Jr. (D-15) voted for the final version of the welfare-reform 
bill, The Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Act (H.R. 
3734) in the U.S. House of Representatives last week.  The 
legislation turns over large block grants to the states and sharply 
limits the eligibility of able-bodied individuals who do not have 
dependents.
<p>
Under the measure, the current Aid to Families with Dependent 
Children is converted to a block grant program, giving states the 
flexibility and discretion to design programs that work best in their 
region. The bill also sets a five-year lifetime limit on welfare 
benefits (with few exceptions) and cuts off Food Stamp benefits to 
able-bodied adults between the ages of 18 and 50 and who have no 
dependents to three months out of every three years. 
<p>
"Yesterday's package sends a message of independence and 
responsibility," said Rep. McHale.  "Although the bill is not a 
perfect piece of legislation, it is the first chance in decades for 
real change in the current system which fosters dependency and is 
neither affordable for taxpayers nor humane for its recipients."
<p>
Fox said that welfare reform  "will be remembered as one of the major 
accomplishments of this session of Congress. Today we have opened he 
door to a better, more productive life for men, women and children 
who have been trapped by a life of dependency in our current welfare 
system.  
<p>
Fox said that the bill continues the current guarantee of health 
coverage during the transitional period between welfare and work for 
families.  The transitional period was scheduled to expire in 1998, 
but the legislation extends it to 2001.  
<p>
McHale said that he had not voted for the first two versions of the 
bill that had come before the House "because I felt they were 
unnecessarily harsh toward children.  Most of those hard edges have 
now been smoothed off the bill, leaving behind legislation that i 
feel is an important first step toward ending dependency upon the 
Federal government while providing a helping hand for those in 
transition."
<p>
"I am pleased that several important provisions were added or 
improves upon in the final version of the bill," said McHale, who 
added, "Medicaid is protected from unreasonable cuts and the school 
lunch program will be protected contrary to what Speaker Newt 
Gingrich urged just a year ago."
<p>
A spokesman from Speaker's office said that Rep. Gingrich had 
advocated a lesser increase -- 4 1/2 percent per year, --  than the 
6.5 % increase favored by Congressional Democrats. The spokesman said 
that Speaker Gingrich had never proposed any cuts in the school lunch 
program.

<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
</html>
