<body>
<title>The Hearthstone Press: Editorial, July 17, 1996</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Editorial -- Remove Limits From Campaign Contributions
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>


	Last week's editorial took up the outright unfairness and 
inaccuracy of a radio ad about Medicare that now plays frequently on 
Philadelphia area radio stations -- an ad which assails non-existent 
"cuts" and characterizes a $500 per child tax credit as "tax cuts 
mostly for the rich." The ad begins with a statement, required by 
campaign laws, of who pays for the ad: the AFL-CIO. If there ever were 
a good example of how federal laws regulating election campaigns have 
failed, this is it. 
<p>
	Current campaign finance laws prohibit individuals from giving 
more than $1,000 to any one candidate, but people can easily get 
around that limit by either giving to as many PAC's (political action 
committees) or lobby organizations as they like, and then the PAC's 
themselves can give to candidates. While it is a common practice among 
candidates to decry one's opponent's acceptance of PAC contributions, 
most candidates are heavily dependent on PAC's because the limits on 
individual giving simply makes it impossible to do without them and 
still have enough money to win elections. And because there can be 
many PAC's representing the same special interest, there is really no 
limit at all to the influence these PAC's can wield together. Does it 
do any good at all to substitute PAC influence for the influence an 
individual might wish to have?
<p>
	Topping PAC's, however, are labor unions, which can collect dues 
from members who may or may not share the political views of their 
leadership, and which can then use those dues to pay for ads targeted 
at individual congressional seats -- in this case, the Thirteenth 
District, occupied by Jon Fox. The AFL-CIO ad uses all of the language 
in the script of the Democratic Party playbook, but it triggers no 
alarms in the campaign laws. While congressional candidates might be 
able to match each other's contributions from PAC's and individuals, 
it is much more difficult to come up with enough money to counter a 
union ad campaign backed by $40 million in dues. 
<p>
	What's the solution to all this? The problem with any muzzle that 
might be devised to limit union spending would also be a restraint of 
free speech, and even if limits could be put on the total amount of 
money a candidate might accept or spend, unions can still provide 
political campaigns with "soft dollar" contributions of office space 
and manpower. A better idea would be to take all limits from what 
anyone -- individual or political organization -- may give, so a 
candidate with popular ideas can attract contributions to pay for ads 
countering his or her opponent's. The only requirement should be that 
candidates disclose the source and amount of all support they receive, 
in money or in kind, so voters can know who pays for the campaign, 
foul or fair.   

<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
</html>
 
