<html>
<body>
<title>The Real Mediscare</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
The Real Mediscare
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>


	Want to know what it was like to be on the Titanic?  Sit back and 
watch while Medicare goes broke in front of your eyes.
<p>
	Medicare Part A provides coverage for care provided in hospitals 
and other facilities.  The Medicare Trust Fund, which is the account 
which pays the medical bills is quickly, not slowly- QUICKLY- going 
broke.  How quickly?  Last year, the Trustees of the Fund, who are 
primarily appointed by President Clinton, said the fund would go broke 
in the year 2002.  This year, President Clinton's panel says the fund 
will go broke in the year 2001.
<p>
	The S.S. Medicare has hit the iceberg and she's going down fast.
<p>
	Is something being done to avert this catastrophe?  Well it's a 
remarkable thing.  The Republicans are trying to lower the lifeboats 
and get the passengers to safety, while the Democrats seem to be 
cutting holes in the lifeboats and telling the passengers don't worry, 
the hole in the boat can be fixed with duct tape.
<p>
	Now you might think that because I'm a Republican I'm being 
partisan.  Well, consider the following sequence of events that 
occurred just recently.  The Congressional Budget Office announced 
that the Medicare program is going broke faster than predicted.  The 
Republicans immediately announced a new plan to preserve Medicare, 
scaling back significantly the plan offered last year.
<p>
	When the President's own Medicare Trustees confirmed the bad news, 
the President called on the Republicans to meet with him.  The 
President said that his plan and the Republican Plan really aren't 
that far apart.  Now this sounds like we have a breakthrough, right?  
Sounds like we might actually see some progress, right?
<p>
	At the same time, the President's crewmen- the Democratic 
leadership in Congress- are again accusing the Republicans of offering 
a plan that cuts Medicare to finance a tax cut for the rich.  That's 
funny, I thought the President said his plan and the Republican plan 
were not far apart.
<p>
	Then the President's own Secretary of Health and Human Services, 
Donna Shalala, states flatly that there will be no significant changes 
permitted to the Medicare program by this administration.
<p>
	If you attended Congressman McHale's recent Town Meeting you heard 
a good example of the Democratic nonsense on this issue when you heard 
him say that his Republican opponent is "against Medicare." 
<p>
	The real "Mediscare" is the way in which Medicare Part A is going 
broke while the Democrats refuse to consider the real reforms 
necessary to save Medicare.  Just adding 5 or 7 years to the life of 
the program, which is what the plans of both parties will do, is not 
going to cut it.
<p>
	In the year 2010, the first "baby boomers" will turn 65.  When that 
happens it will be like the ocean water reaching the deck chairs.  
Fixing the hole in the boat will not be enough.
<p>
	There is an old saying about how an ounce of prevention is worth a 
pound of cure.  Well, if we don't put the rhetoric aside and enact the 
ounces of prevention now- real reform of the Medicare program- then 
our senior citizens are going to be pounded by the cure.

<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
</html>

