<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/townhall/columnists/otb/TN/anderson22.html 204.71.237.74 19970108130946 text/html 8832
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 13:09:59 GMT
Last-modified: Wednesday, 11-Sep-96 20:19:55 GMT
Content-length: 8643
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>
Outside the Beltway - Chatanooga Free Press
</title>
</head>
<body background="/townhall/background.jpg bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h2>Chatanooga Free Press</h2>
<i>9/04/96</i>
<P>
<P><b>Choice Makes Things Better</b><P>
 It used to be so simple. We sent our children to our neighborhood   
school. They could usually walk. They knew everybody. We knew their   
teachers. Most kids did pretty well, or if there were problems the report   
cards and the teachers alerted us to try to take remedial action. Costs   
were not exorbitant and educational results were generally pretty   
good.<P>Nowadays, we spend lots more on education, but honest evaluation   
has brought distressing awakening to the fact that for the first time in   
our history, we have a generation less well educated than the one before   
it!<P>What's wrong?<P>Lots of things. The main fault is not the schools'. The   
biggest problem is the deterioration of our social fabric, with broken   
homes, lack of parental support to encourage and discipline, single   
mothers with the stressful necessity to earn a living and look after the   
children without help.<P>But there are other factors, too. Much of it began   
with forced busing of kids out of their neighborhoods for social   
engineering. It disrupted parental support and influence, not to mention   
the diversion of school money from teaching to transporting. There also   
has been the ""dumbing down'' of intellectual standards.<P>Shockingly,   
there also have been peer pressures <i>against</i> getting a good   
education. Instead of having ""honor rolls'' effectively stimulating   
better results, there have been strong peer pressures in some   
circumstances demanding students </i>not </i>work and attain, to avoid   
being a ""nerd.'' Just shuffle along and be ""one of the boys,''   
non-attainers have told their classmates, making them non-attainers,   
too.<P>Still, there are many parents and many students who do want the best   
education possible. They know that's the key to their personal future.   
Experience has proved abundantly that most of us do better when we can   
have our own choice along with challenge. That is especially true of   
schools. If parents and children get the schools they want, better   
results are likely.<P>School ""choice'' may be the best way out of our   
education morass. <P>When did the greatest positive gain in American   
education take place? It came in the years just after World War II. What   
caused it? The GI Bill of Rights!<P>Our government thanked the war   
veterans, and helped make up for the dangers and disruptions in life that   
they had faced, by providing tuition for them to go to school _ wherever   
they wanted to go to legitimate schools.<P>Many went to public   
institutions, like the University of Tennessee. Some went to independent   
schools, such as the University of Chattanooga was at that time. Some   
chose church-related schools, ranging from Catholic Notre Dame to   
Southern Methodist to Baptist Carson Newman. There was no public-private   
or church-state issue because each grant was made to an<i>   
individual</i> _ and he made his own, personal choice. Many did well.   
Our nation quickly became a much better-educated nation.<P>Why not do the   
same for all school children? Why not allot each student his or her share   
of tax money for education in the form of an ""opportunity scholarship.''   
Then let each family use it to pay the full cost or partial cost of   
whatever school each person chose to attend?<P>That would allow countless   
""poor'' kids to escape imprisonment in inferior schools. It would spark   
the creation of new independent schools at reasonable cost. It would let   
people whose means ordinarily would bar them from aspirations at costly   
private schools to make the leap to attend them if they chose to do so.   
It would inspire existing public schools to provide quality that would be   
appealing to people in their neighborhoods.<P>If parents and children could   
make the choice, the results would surely be better. We'd get more for   
our tax dollars.<P>The GI Bill proved what works. So why not let it work   
for the benefit of all our children?/l
<P>
<b>Mr. Clinton's Costly Train Ride</b><P>
 It was a brilliant political idea. While the Democratic National   
Convention was going through its not-quite-exciting early sessions last   
month, President Bill Clinton and Vice President Al Gore boarded a   
government-subsidized train for a ""whistle-stop'' ride over four days,   
generating enthusiastic public cheering sections at each stop, with   
plenty of photo ops and lots of free publicity.<P>But the publicity was all   
that was ""free.'' And the big cost was not just from taxpayer   
subsidization of the train. The big cost involved Mr. Clinton's   
promises.<P>Republican National Chairman Haley Barbour figures that the   
train ride covered 671 miles _ and that along the way, Mr. Clinton   
promised $10 billion in programs for new government spending of our tax   
money, even as budgets remain unbalanced and national debt is rising near   
$5.2 trillion.<P>Mr. Barbour calculated that Mr. Clinton's new promises for   
new spending averaged<i> ""$15 million of our own money for every single   
mile of his trip''</i>   to Chicago.<P>""I'm glad they didn't have their   
convention in San Francisco,'' Mr. Barbour said.<P>If Mr. Clinton is   
promising that kind of new spending for new programs on his way to   
hoped-for re-election, how much do you think he will spend _ and tax _ if   
he wins a second term, with no restraints of ever having to face the   
voters and taxpayers again?
<P>
<b>Welfare Reform "Reform</b><P>
 The biggest and most costly failure of governmental policy in the   
history of our nation has been what we call ""welfare.''<P>Born of   
compassion for the poor and needy, "welfare'' came to be a network of   
programs costing many billions of dollars.<P>Welfare has not removed many   
people from poverty. But it has encouraged millions to become permanently   
dependent on the dole. It has destroyed families, undermined character,   
promoted the flight of fathers, led to the impoverishment of women,   
caused deprivation for children, subsidized teen and other pregnancies   
without marriage, and even increased rewards for repeated immoral   
mistakes.<P>The ravages of welfare failure have been evident for many   
years, victimizing both recipients and the taxpayers. But remedies were   
discouraged because it was politically risky to interfere with the   
customary receipt of some government check or service. There developed a   
constituency of "entitled'' people who made reformers gun-shy.<P>Finally,   
however, the mess became so bad that that enough conservatives were   
elected to Congress to try to address the problem, to try at last to   
"reform'' welfare.<P>The basic plan _ surprise _ was to begin to do what   
the Constitution has prescribed all along, make it all a responsibility   
of the states or the people, not the federal government.<P>Congress   
dutifully passed a welfare-reform bill.<P>President Bill Clinton,   
predictably, vetoed it.<P>Congress passed another welfare-reform bill.<P>But   
Mr. Clinton vetoed that, too.<P>Congress passed a third welfare-reform   
bill.<P>Mr. Clinton was inclined to issue a third veto, yielding to the   
demands of his fellow liberals. But along came Dick Morris, Mr. Clinton's   
since-disgraced master guru of political opportunism. He urged Mr.   
Clinton to sign, to appeal for conservatives' votes, since his liberal   
supporters had nowhere else to go.<P>Mr. Clinton signed.<P>That has fooled   
some "moderates,'' and even some "conservatives,'' into thinking maybe   
"old Bill isn't so radical after all.''<P>But "Slick Willie,'' with the   
ink from signing still fresh on his pen, began to hint that his heart   
wasn't really in it _ that if re-elected, he'd "reform'' the "welfare   
reform'' to suit the liberals. <P>The welfare-reform bill that has been   
enacted promisesd improvement. It is not perfect, not a full solution.   
It's just a start. A lot of state trial-and-error-and-adjustment will be   
needed. But it should not be undercut.<P>Voters, who have paid billions of   
dollars for failure, need to be aware that there are some people who want   
to go back to old-style "welfare.'' Watch out for liberal saboteurs.
<P>
</body>
</html>


