<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- Why Do We Care?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Harry Beck And The Rest Of Us
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Friday, September 6, 1996 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
Harry Beck was an electrical worker for an East Coast power company and
belonged to a labor union. But he became dissatisfied with its activities,
particularly in using union funds taken from him and others for political
candidates and causes he did not believe in.
<p>
As an individual, he couldn't do much about it. He could be fired if he
didn't pay tribute to the union bosses. Many American workers are in the
same boat if they live in one of the 29 states that do not have
right-to-work laws. Right-to-work laws let individuals decide for
themselves for or against joining and paying a union, without being denied
a job or being fired if they decide not to join and pay.
<p>
Mr. Beck decided he didn't want to belong to the union. He managed to hold
onto his job but only by continuing to pay dues.
<p>
Backed by the National Right to Work Foundation, Mr. Beck protested. Why
should he, not belonging to a union, be forced to pay for union political
activities that he disagreed with?
<p>
His lawsuit in support of his position labored through many years and many
appeals to a final ruling by the Supreme Court of the United States. It
said he didn't have to pay the union for anything not connected with the
collective bargaining process, and that he was entitled to a refund of his
forced payments.
<p>
That was a big victory. But if the court had been 100 percent right, it
would have said he didn't have to pay anything to any organization he did
not want to join. Nevertheless, the Supreme Court's ruling in the Beck case
was a very important one for all Americans.
<p>
It should set all workers free from union shakedown, shouldn't it?
<p>
Well, it should, but it hasn't. Word about the rights of workers under the
Beck ruling has been slow getting around. A conspiracy between union bosses
and pro-union government agents has discouraged dissemination of news about
the rights Harry Beck helped to win.
<p>
For example, the top prosecutor for the federal government's National Labor
Relations Board (NLRB) ruled a few months ago that employers violate
federal law if they inform their employees of their right to keep their own
money and not have it used for union politics!
<p>
That's what NLRB General Counsel Fred Feinstein said.
<p>
It's not surprising why. The AFL-CIO has announced it is going to collect
$35 million from its members to finance a huge political campaign to
re-elect President Bill Clinton and try to weed conservatives out of
Congress, replacing them with rubber-stamp liberals favoring increased
union-boss power.
<p>
Do you think it is right for any American to be forced to join any
organization to get and hold a job to support his family?
<p>
Do you think it is right for anyone to force a worker to help finance
political activities he doesn't agree with? The Supreme Court doesn't. But
the Clinton administration and the NLRB general counsel think it's just
fine.
<p>
This is just one of many examples of how basic American freedom is being
tyrannically overridden by political dictators who, so far, are getting
away with it.
<p>
They expect to do even better if Mr. Clinton is re-elected with a Congress
subservient to him and them.
<p>
<br>

<i>Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press</i>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
