http://www.cpac.org:80/townhall/columnists/otb/TN/anderson20.html 204.71.237.74 19970108131018 text/html 5844
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 13:10:26 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 05-Sep-96 20:08:06 GMT
Content-length: 5656
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- Why Do We Care?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Why Do We Care?
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Thursday, September 5, 1996 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
There is a long and proper tradition in our country that whenever Americans
are committed to military action, we "rally 'round the flag,' whatever
differences may otherwise prevail.
<p>
And when our military people go into harm's way, whatever the cause, we
"rally 'round our airmen, sailors and soldiers.'
<p>
Those reactions have been prevalent this week as President Bill Clinton has
sent air strikes with cruise missiles against barbaric Saddam Hussein's
Iraq.
<p>
But while giving patriotic support for American policy and people in
military action, many Americans reasonably have begun to ask: Exactly
what's going on? What is our purpose? What is our policy? Why do we care?
<p>
These questions deserve thoughtful and frank answers.
<p>
Saddam Hussein, of course, is a disgusting, murderous dictator. But we do
not automatically go to war against every disgusting, murderous dictator.
<p>
This week's attacks were triggered when Saddam moved to support one faction
of Kurds within his country against another faction of Kurds, all of whom
want independence in a unified Kurdistan -- along with many Kurds in
neighboring Iran and Turkey.
<p>
Saddam from time to time has engaged in genocidal attacks on the Kurds,
including civilian children and women. But there is more involved in our
military action than concern for the Kurds.
<p>
Though President Clinton has committed American troops to intervention in
Haiti and Bosnia (neither case being justified by acute U.S. national
interests), it is not our nation's policy to take military action in every
troublespot in the world where unconscionable victimization of some element
occurs.
<p>
There are two real, overriding reasons for U.S. intervention: One is
"power." The other is "oil." (They may seem to be the same.)
<p>
We must not allow Saddam -- or anyone else -- to wield destabilizing,
dictatorial power in the Middle East, threatening the whole world.
<p>
Saddam made himself intolerable when he seized Kuwait and threatened to
invade Saudi Arabia. He dreams of becoming a modern Nebuchadnezzar, master
of all the Middle East, either by direct military occupation or through the
power to poise a sword of Damocles over his neighbors' heads, forcing them
to dance obediently to his tune. The United States correctly cannot allow
such a dictator to control the Middle East.
<p>
Cynics, of course, sneer, saying the only real reason for American
intervention against Saddam is "oil." Yes, oil is a very important
consideration. But that does not justify their cynicism.
<p>
Some who sneer that we are motivated by oil policy alone ignore the fact
that oil does "make the world go 'round.' Saddam sits on a huge oil field.
So do his neighbors, whom he would like to dominate. The United States,
Western Europe and Japan are affected in large measure by what happens to
Middle East oil. Whoever controls the great Middle East pool of oil can
have a very large impact on our prices, our economy and our way of life.
<p>
We obviously cannot permit Saddam to have the power to govern our economic
welfare and that of other nations throughout the world.
<p>
Those who sneer about U.S. sensitivity to oil would be the first to cry out
in complaint if their car gas tank ran dry and they could not get a refill,
if gasoline prices skyrocketed, if they lost their jobs because their
employers could not get the oil needed as a raw material and to keep the
wheels of industry turning.
<p>
It is sickening that we have allowed Saddam to remain in threatening power
as long as we have. We were right in intervening against Saddam's
aggression in Kuwait. Our forces were brilliant in winning the Persian Gulf
War. Our policy was stupid, or worse, in failing to finish Desert Storm
with total victory, ousting Saddam, and ending all military threats from
Iraq. As a result of that failure, Saddam remains the problem we are
addressing today.
<p>
There surely will be no renewal of U.S. military ground action against
Saddam under current circumstances. The air blows are designed to minimize
his mischief and to keep him on a short leash. No final, total,
satisfactory solution is in sight at a price we are willing to pay.
Obviously, we long for internal Iraqi dissatisfaction to lead eventually to
the removal of Saddam. (But we have qualms that whoever replaces him may
also be bad.)
<p>
The United States cannot ignore Saddam and his part of the world. We
condemn his atrocities against people under his control. We deplore his
rule-or-ruin megalomania. We are uneasy that he in Iraq and the ayatollahs
who rule in Iran are the primary, temporarily stalemating, dominant forces
in their part of the world.
<p>
We should understand that the flow -- or non-flow -- of oil in the Persian
Gulf area has a far more acute impact upon our personal and national
welfare than many people realize.
<p>
We are doing now what we have to do -- lest we face worse that we do not
want to do.
<p>
<br>

<i>Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press</i>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
