<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- Are Our Blows Too Soft?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Are Our Blows Too Soft?
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Wednesday, September 4, 1996 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
The United States has fired two waves of cruise missiles at Iraqi targets
within 24 hours to punish Saddam Hussein for his renewed aggression. But
have we hit him hard enough? Have we picked the right targets?
<p>
Saddam surely has gotten the message that the United States is displeased
with his new aggression against the Kurds in northern Iraq. But have we
only "stung' him when we should have delivered a far more destructive blow?
<p>
In the first attack, 27 satellite-guided cruise missiles were fired from
two B-52 bombers and U.S. Navy ships.
<p>
In the second strike, called a "mop-up' operation to get missed targets, 17
cruise missiles were launched from three Navy ships and a submarine.
<p>
The targets were identified as air-defense facilities, command-and-control
installations, air-launch missile sites and radar positions. It was
explained that destruction of such facilities would make it more difficult
for Saddam to carry out his ordered attacks against U.S. aircraft that will
be patrolling "no-fly' zones to keep Iraqi aircraft grounded.
<p>
But while Saddam certainly doesn't like to have any of his equipment
damaged or destroyed, those are relatively minor targets compared with the
much more important Iraqi military installations that were not hit.
<p>
We have shown Saddam we will strike. But we also have shown that we will
pull our punches. That sort of thing may embolden an angry Saddam rather
than make him shiver in fear.
<p>
We certainly are not about to undertake a new Desert Storm, nor should we.
If common sense prevails, the United States will commit no ground forces to
any new action against Saddam. But if Saddam's provocations are sufficient
to justify any American military action _ and they are _ our punitive
strikes should be targeted sufficiently to be emphatic and deterring.
<p>
We are afraid the selected targets of our 44 cruise missiles were peanuts
compared with what we might have hit.
<p>
In too many U.S. military operations since World War II, we have pulled
punches and taken half-way measures, stopping short of the fully desired
effect.
<p>
That Saddam remains in power after his defeat in Desert Storm is one very
embarrassing proof of this.
<p>
We have hindered some Iraqi defenses against our aircraft. We have extended
a "no-fly' zone by one degree, about 60 miles. Overall, what have we done
to Saddam but tell him we are bothered by his continuing military action?
We certainly have done very little to incapacitate him or to increase the
chances that he will be removed from power by internal objections to his
gross and bloody misrule.
<p>
The United States has acted, but perhaps not enough. If we are going to
engage in military operations, we should aim at targets of maximum
importance, not just fringe ones.
<p>
<br>

<i>Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press</i>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
