<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- Where Do Jobs Come From?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Where Do Jobs Come From?
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Sunday, September 1 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
We all agree that it is important for everyone to have a job. Earning a
living is basic to survival, to personal freedom, to the welfare of our
nation. So naturally, everyone should want to do the things that create
jobs and offer better opportunities.
<p>
With those goals, it is important to know where jobs come from. The simple
answer is that in the United States, most jobs, by far, are created by
small businesses.
<p>
That being the case, everyone should be an advocate of small business.
<p>
The kind of presidential leadership that we have has a tremendous influence
on small business and its promotion or hindrance.
<p>
That's why the Republican National Committee is calling attention to the
record of President Bill Clinton in that respect.
<p>
It notes that Mr. Clinton:
<p>
<ul>
<li> "(C)lobbered small businesses with his $250 billion tax hike in 1993."
<li> Vetoed Republican attempts to lower the inheritance tax -- "the biggest
reason for the break-up of family farms and businesses."
<li> Vetoed a capital-gains tax cut and a home-office deduction for small
business owners.
<li> "(V)etoed Republican attempts to allow small businesses to establish
simple 401(k) retirement plans for their employees."
<li> Vetoed the Balanced Budget Act, which would have brought lower interest
rates for small business improvements.
<li> Proposed a single-payer, government-run health system that would have
imposed a 7.9 percent payroll tax on small businesses.
<li> Blocked regulatory reform, although in three years of the Clinton
administration 188,725 pages of regulations were added in the Federal
Register, while employing a record-high 128,566 regulatory bureaucrats.
</ul>
<p>
By contrast, the Republicans list these positions of Sen. Bob Dole as a
presidential alternative. He would:
<p>
<ul>
<li> Support tax improvements to aid small businesses in obtaining capital for
growth, a plan passed by Congress but vetoed by Mr. Clinton.
<li> Create an Interagency Regulatory Sunsetting Task Force to review
regulations for discard.
<li> Favor health-care reform enabling the self-employed to deduct 80 percent
of their health-insurance premiums, and allowing small businesses with 50
or fewer employees to open tax-free Medical Savings Accounts, a plan Mr.
Clinton has blocked.
<li> Stop any proposed regulation from taking effect for 60 days, allowing
time for Congress to override burdensome rules.
</ul>
<p>
These items, like many others, show the basic Clinton philosophy is for
more and bigger government, while the Dole philosophy is for more personal
freedom and small-business promotion for more and better jobs.
<p>
The contrasting effects of those philosophies are important for all
Americans to understand.
<p>
<br>

<i>Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press</i>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
