<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000253-B044-59</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/townhall/columnists/otb/TN/anderson15.html 204.71.237.74 19970108131123 text/html 10478
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 13:11:40 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 30-Aug-96 19:22:32 GMT
Content-length: 10291
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- "You Have No Character"</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
"You Have No Character"
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Friday, Aug. 30 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
In its current issue, Time magazine spotlighted President Bill Clinton's
until-now-little-known political scripter, Dick Morris. The magazine could
not have known it was giving a preview of Mr. Morris' appearance this week
in the news spotlight -- and how it would reflect upon President Bill
Clinton.
<p>
Mr. Morris has played both sides of the political street. Sometimes he has
masterminded campaigns for very liberal Democratic candidates and sometimes
for very conservative Republicans.
<p>
The Time report told of a Morris luncheon meeting with Bush administration
strategist Roger Ailes. Mr. Morris reportedly told Mr. Ailes: "We should
work together; I know how to beat the Democrats.'
<p>
But Mr. Ailes responded: "I don't want to work with you. You have no
character.'
<p>
"That afternoon,' Time said, "a friend asked Morris how his lunch had gone.
"It was good,' Morris replied. "He told me I had no character. I really
learned a lot."
<p>
But obviously Mr. Morris had not learned enough. It was not Time magazine
that had Mr. Morris' primary attention this week. It was a story in the
grocery tabloid the Star, the sheet that four years ago exposed then-Gov.
Bill Clinton's 12-year affair with Gennifer Flowers.
<p>
The Star reported that Mr. Morris, President Clinton's friend for nearly
two decades and his most intimate current political adviser, was involved
with a $200-an-hour prostitute -- with whom Mr. Morris shared intimate
information about the Clinton campaign, let her listen in on Morris-Clinton
telephone conversations, gave her copies of Democratic National Convention
speeches by Mrs. Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vice President Al Gore a couple
of days before they actually delivered them, and spoke to her of Mrs.
Clinton as "the Twister' and of Mr. Clinton as "the Monster.'
<p>
With Mr. Clinton poised for his triumphant speech accepting the Democratic
presidential nomination when the embarrassing story broke, Mr. Morris
hastily resigned, denounced those who told the story -- but pointedly did
not deny it. Then he disappeared, reportedly heading back home to his wife.
<p>
Obviously, that was an unscripted disruption in Mr. Clinton's riding-high
campaign. But what does it have to do with Mr. Clinton?
<p>
The point is that in recent weeks, it has been the voice of Mr. Morris that
came out whenever Mr. Clinton opened his mouth.
<p>
Mr. Morris is given credit for Mr. Clinton's political comeback that has
gained the president large leads in polls. Mr. Clinton did what Mr. Morris
advised, making a phony shift from being a real liberal to masquerading as
a "conservative.'
<p>
Do the American people like being fooled? Do the American people know that
Mr. Morris and Mr. Clinton have been fooling them?
<p>
Mr. Clinton spoke of the scandal and Mr. Morris' departure in these words:
"Dick Morris is my friend and he is a superb political strategist.' He is,
indeed. But what about "character'?
<p>
* Is Mr. Morris' lack of character more reprehensible than Mr. Clinton's
lack of character in following Mr. Morris' scheme for a chameleon-like
appearance change in political philosophy?
<p>
* Is what has been revealed about Mr. Morris' immoral activities worse than
what has been revealed about Mr. Clinton's involvement with Gennifer
Flowers and others? Why did the revelations about Mr. Morris cost him his
job but the revelations about Mr. Clinton were followed by his election as
president?
<p>
* And what about Mr. Clinton's judgment -- picking Mr. Morris to mastermind
his campaign, then pretending to be what he is not? Is that
"presidential-quality' judgment?
<p>
Mr. Morris obviously is without convictions and character. But the words
that have been coming out of Mr. Clinton have been the words of Mr. Morris.
<p>
Mr. Morris for president? Or Mr. Clinton for president? Or who can tell the
difference?
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
Mr. Clinton's Speech
</h3>
</center>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

President Bill Clinton made a good speech last night.
<p>
He praised all "good" things, and claimed credit for most of them. He
condemned all "bad' things, and promised to fix them. How could anyone
argue with that?
<p>
The problem is that the picture he presented is distorted. Some of the
things he claimed credit for -- welfare reform and medical-care legislation,
for example -- are things he had fought tooth and toenail. He vetoed
welfare-reform twice, before signing a third bill. He opposed the medical
bill until he saw passage handwriting on the congressional wall. He claimed
he had fought crime by putting 100,000 policemen on the streets, though
only about 20,000 are now on duty. He boasted of family leave for "12
million' Americans, though fewer than one-fourth that many have been
involved. He again falsely labeled conservatives' policies on Medicare as
"cuts' -- although their proposal was to increase funding 7 percent. There
were more misrepresentations. But who can stop and check such details in
mid-speech, especially when the words sound warm and good and positive?
<p>
Mr. Clinton surely won points when he said of his opponents whom he
misrepresented: "But I will not attack; I will not attack them personally,
or permit others to do it in this party if I can prevent it. Thank you.
Thank you.'
<p>
Mr. Clinton knew he was on a popular theme when he made big promises for
education. Though the Constitution bars the federal government from
education, leaving it to the states and the people, he outlined lots of
new, big federal spending for education -- a $1,500 tuition tax credit, a
scholarship for the first two years of college, a $10,000 deduction for
college tuition, a tax-free education IRA, a $2,600 grant for an unemployed
or underemployed person to get training, plus "mobilization' of 30,000
reading specialists to rally an army of a million reading tutors.
<p>
He has ridiculed Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole's plan to cut
taxes, cut spending and balance the budget, but he proposed tax cuts,
spending increases and budget balance -- though he has roadblocked
congressional efforts to require balance by 2002.
<p>
He also offered to guarantee no capital-gains tax -- ever -- on sale of a
home.
<p>
"I want to balance the budget with real cuts in government, in waste,' Mr.
Clinton said, despite listing before and during his speech lots of new
spending programs.
<p>
"My plan gives Americans tax cuts that will help our economy grow,' he
said. That's what Sen. Dole has proposed -- and Mr. Clinton has ridiculed.
<p>
"Let me say again, every tax cut I call for tonight is targeted,' Mr.
Clinton said. He has clearly targeted unequal tax favors, adding to
countless inequities already in effect, making our tax burdens even more
unfair.
<p>
Mr. Clinton's speech was carefully written and artfully delivered. It
reflected clearly the "kinder and gentler' moderate "conservatism' that is
the camouflage which suddenly departed political strategist Dick Morris has
coached Mr. Clinton in adopting.
<p>
Mr. Clinton exuded such confidence that he appeared to feel he already had
his feet on the steps of the platform, ready to be sworn in as president a
second time.
<p>
With great poise and benign smile, Mr. Clinton said he wants to build "a
bridge to the 21st century.' That might seem appealing -- unless listeners
compare his ethereal predictions with his liberal philosophy, his personal
character and his record of choosing to begin his current administration
with encouragement of homosexuals in the military, followed by the biggest
tax increase in American history, with spending rising, government growing
and personal freedom being reduced.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
A Clinton, Gore Difference
</h3>
</center>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>


President Bill Clinton and Vice President Al Gore embraced each other and
boasted about each other repeatedly this week. Mr. Clinton is running for
president now. Mr. Gore is running for 2000. They might seem to be "two
peas in a pod.' But there is a difference.
<p>
Mr. Clinton doesn't really, fervently believe in any philosophy -- except
whatever it takes to win. But Mr. Gore is a real liberal -- honestly
believing in and devoting himself to that faulty philosophy. Mr. Gore
really means it.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
Whose Convention?
</h3>
</center>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>


It was the Democratic National Convention that made news in Chicago this
week. But actually, who ruled the convention?
<p>
Obviously, President Bill Clinton heads the list. But among the delegates,
what influences were greatest?
<p>
Very prominent, of course, were the union bosses of the AFL-CIO, who have
promised to shake down both willing members and unwilling captive members
and others to collect $35 million to promote Mr. Clinton and liberal
Democratic aspirants to Congress.
<p>
The teachers unions were big, with about 700 delegates. The radical
national leaders and policies of the teachers unions are, as Sen. Bob Dole
pointedly emphasized in his presidential-nomination acceptance speech,
quite different from most teachers and their views on the local school
level.
<p>
The organized trial lawyers were on hand to reward Mr. Clinton for vetoing
legislation that would limit their exorbitant damage judgments.
<p>
The NAACP and ACLU types and activists of other liberal organizations were
out in force.
<p>
These are the folks behind Mr. Clinton's pose of "moderation.'
<p>
<br>

<i>Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press</i>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
