<DOCNO>WT19-B19-194</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA024-000253-B044-84</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/townhall/columnists/otb/TN/anderson14.html 204.71.237.74 19970108131132 text/html 9957
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 13:11:50 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 29-Aug-96 19:22:28 GMT
Content-length: 9769
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- Mr. Clinton Triumphant</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Mr. Clinton Triumphant
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Wednesday, Aug. 28 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
President Bill Clinton whistle-stopped his way into Chicago, and to certain
presidential nomination triumph at the Democratic National Convention, in a
manner typical of his administration for the past four years and what we
may expect if he is elected for four more years.
<p>
He was riding on a taxpayer-subsidized railroad, stopping at every
opportunity to show his friendly smile, promising some new program at
taxpayers' expense to every constituency where tax money might buy him
votes.
<p>
His four-day, 559-mile trek left him hoarse but enthusiastic as he
continued to work on his acceptance speech tonight -- that aides said will
offer still more promises.
<p>
He wrapped it all up by declaring: "We can be responsible with your money,
we can be strong for your economy, we can be tough on crime. But we can
still have a heart for those who need the heart of America, that are too
often left behind and forgotten.'
<p>
But do most Americans want Mr. Clinton & Co. to be "responsible' with our
money, or do our people prefer for government to be limited, allowing our
people to be responsible with their own money instead of continuing and
increasing the big-government welfare state?
<p>
His train trip cost much more than whatever the amount of taxpayer subsidy
the government provided. He promised at least $8.5 billion more in spending
to impose more gun control, to curb domestic abuse, to improve children's
reading, to clean up toxic wastes, to provide medical care, to assure
nutritional programs, to give more child care for the poor, to undo some of
the reform of welfare that he grudgingly had signed.
<p>
Many of those things are not constitutionally federal-government
responsibilities. But the whole Clinton philosophy involves high taxes,
bigger federal spending, more governmental bureaucracy and regulations,
promoting citizen dependency upon government rather than personal
independence and freedom.
<p>
Ironically, most Americans seem to be speaking up for less government, less
taxing, less spending, balanced budgets, and ending the growth of the huge
national debt -- while embracing Mr. Clinton and more government, more
taxing, more spending, unbalanced budgets and bigger national debt.
<p>
No wonder Mr. Clinton is confident. He'll put it all on display again
tonight.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
What Jobs?
</h3>
</center>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>
Strongly ridiculing welfare-reform efforts to get people off the dole and
into jobs, former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo has been speaking up in and
around the Democratic National Convention to ridicule the work efforts.
"What jobs?' he asks.
<p>
He assumes no jobs are available.
<p>
But in many places, including our own community, there are immigrants --
some legal and some illegal -- who are working at good-paying if not plush
jobs within walking distance of the residences of non-working American
citizens who are getting welfare checks, and have been getting them for
years.
<p>
Why is it that some people who do not even speak our language fluently can
find work and function in this country while millions of Americans seem
unable to find jobs?
<p>
The answer is that the immigrants really want to earn a living, while some
Americans prefer not to take jobs as long as taxpayers hand out checks for
not working.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
Incivility And Indecency
</h3>
</center>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>


Unfortunately, our social fabric has deteriorated to the point where
differences in viewpoint are too often expressed with incivility, even
disorder and violence.
<p>
And this trend often leads to indecency.
<p>
Lewd and disgusting signs, symbols and language abound.
<p>
Some moviemakers claim people don't want to see "G' movies -- so they take G
movies and inject gratuitous profanity or sex or violence, or all three,
just to get a rating that seems to make movies more commercially appealing.
<p>
Words that used to stir debate as to whether they should even be included
in dictionaries now pepper almost every paragraph of some of the
best-selling books.
<p>
Situations so disgusting and degrading that one wonders how their authors
even thought of them have become almost standard fare.
<p>
People you know and would expect to be clean of speech may be using
expressions that are lewd -- but are so common that many people who resort
to them are unaware of what they are really saying.
<p>
There may have been one example of that in Chicago recently. It involved a
woman, and resulted in an extreme reaction.
<p>
The president was passing by. Demonstrating common incivility, a woman
standing nearby with her husband shouted a derogatory expression that
unfortunately is common even among children these days. Did she know what
it really meant? Maybe she did. Maybe she didn't. It was something that
should not pass the lips of anyone. She did not have to like the president,
approve his policies or vote for him. But common (or is it now uncommon?)
courtesy and decency should have sealed her mouth. But nothing restrained
her. She said it. She shouldn't have.
<p>
And that prompted something else that should not have happened. She was
arrested and put in jail!
<p>
Foul speech should be restrained by propriety, not by imprisonment.
<p>
She was shocked. Her husband was shocked. They thought her indecent affront
was acceptable. It should not be. But it should also not be a jailing
offense. She didn't threaten the president. She just degraded herself in
trying to degrade him with bad words.
<p>
The ordinary "cuss words' are not enough for some these days. Many people
like to wallow in really nasty language. And then there are hand signals.
Mere inconvenience in traffic may stir some coarse individuals to resort to
insulting gestures to other motorists. In most cases, the perpetrators know
the gestures mean something derogatory, but some may not really know what
they actually mean. Americans traveling abroad are sometimes warned that
gestures they get away with here may result in violent retaliation if they
resort to them overseas.
<p>
But why is it necessary to use disagreeable, insulting, indecent language
and signs at all? Why not practice self-restraint, courtesy, decency and
civility in our interpersonal affairs -- even when disagreements occur?
<p>
Perhaps if some people really understood what they are saying or signaling
when they resort to all-too-common expressions that are prevalent today,
they would be embarrassed enough to refrain.
<p>
Courtesy and good manners, with consideration for others, are valuable
lubricants that can make otherwise abrasive society work better for all.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
Check This Out!
</h3>
</center>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

Have you heard anyone, even President Bill Clinton, proposing that American
workers be taxed to finance welfare programs for Rio de Janeiro, or to
institute child-care programs in Bangladesh? Have you heard anyone suggest
that American taxpayers ought to pay the medical bills for the people of
Mexico City?
<p>
Of course not! No one suggests that would make sense. But if we are not
called upon to support social programs in foreign nations, why do some
think we ought to take on the financial burdens for them if foreign
citizens come to our country illegally?
<p>
Gov. Pete Wilson of California has majority support but lots of political
critics because he has acted for welfare reform by issuing an order cutting
off benefits for illegal immigrants in his state.
<p>
Why did he do that? It's because illegal invaders have been costing
California taxpayers billions of dollars a year. Cutting off handouts to
illegals should help a little in deterring the wave of millions of illegal
immigrants.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
O.J. -- Right On One Point
</h3>
</center>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

O.J. Simpson is still at it with his public showboating. He went to
Washington this week, where a thousand admirers paid $10 each to hear him
speak at Scripture Cathedral Church.
<p>
No, he did not speak on "Thou shalt not kill.' He spoke to claim that the
American justice system is unfair to blacks. In his case, at least, he's
absolutely right.
<p>
The justice system was totally unfair in giving him "not guilty' verdicts
on the two murder charges arising from the brutal killings of his estranged
wife, Nicole Simpson Brown, and Ron Goldman, a most unfortunate man who
just happened to be at the wrong place when the murderer appeared.
<p>
Simpson enjoyed the news media when he was running with footballs, but
chose to make the news agencies out as villains because of the way they
reported his troubles with law enforcement.
<p>
Facing trial now in a civil suit charging him with wrongful death, and
under a judge's gag order against talking about it, Simpson remained silent
about that. But the testimony yet to come surely will speak more eloquently
than he can.
<p>
<br>

<i>Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press</i>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
