<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- This Is Mr. Clinton's Week</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
This Is Mr. Clinton's Week
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Tuesday, Aug. 27 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
When the Democratic National Convention met four years ago, there seemed to
be little prospect that the presidential candidate it nominated would be a
winner. There was the usual "cheerleading,' but not much confidence.
<p>
The reason, of course, was not just that President George Bush was the
incumbent. Only a few months earlier, he had been riding the crest of an
amazing wave of 90 percent approval resulting from Persian Gulf War victory
enthusiasm.
<p>
Had that not been the case in 1992, the Democrats meeting in Chicago in
1996 might be nominating President Mario Cuomo, or some other Democratic
luminary, for a second term, instead of President Bill Clinton.
<p>
With Mr. Bush so popular in 1992, some Democrats thought they were
nominating a "sacrificial goat' to go through the motions of a political
campaign before Mr. Bush won his second term. That was why some believe
Gov. Cuomo and other Democrats of national status weren't interested in
running.
<p>
But funny things happen in politics.
<p>
Arkansas Gov. Clinton survived the primaries, the Gennifer Flowers
revelations and much, much more. He turned out to be the "hopeless'
Democratic nominee.
<p>
But Mr. Bush's horribly misguided decision to go back on his "Read my lips;
no new taxes' pledge overcame his victory popularity. And then there was a
fellow named Ross Perot who flashed across the political horizon.
<p>
Result: Clinton 43 percent of the vote, Bush 38 percent, Perot 19 percent --
with Mr. Clinton then enjoying inauguration ceremonies and moving into the
White House.
<p>
Mr. Clinton, who had promised tax cuts, inexplicably began his
administration by favoring homosexuals in the armed forces, then demanding
and getting a huge tax increase on everyone.
<p>
Two years later, strong disenchantment with Mr. Clinton, and with Mrs.
Hillary Rodham Clinton and her horribly dictatorial and unpredictably
expensive plan for socialization of medicine, resulted in a mighty surge of
conservatism throughout the country. It elected conservative Republican
majorities in both the Senate and House of Representatives.
<p>
The conservatives did well in pushing sound principles that honestly
reflected what the voters said they wanted. But Congress ran into two
problems: 1. A majority of voters said they wanted one thing, but it turned
out that many didn't want to face the reality of giving up or scaling down
"entitlements' to gain the reduced government, decreased spending and
balanced budgets that they had called for./j 2. Mr. Clinton "out-slicked'
the conservatives, making them appear to be "villains' attacking the
economic interests of the people.
<p>
So President Clinton rides into Chicago this week far from having been a
sacrificial goat. He is a smiling president, lacking serious challenge
within his party, seemingly assured of a second-term victory as he leads
Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole in the polls.
<p>
Sen. Dole is plagued by "image' problems and by the second run of Mr.
Perot, who will surely drain more conservative votes from Sen. Dole than he
will take liberal ones from Mr. Clinton.
<p>
So this is Mr. Clinton's big week as the Democratic National Convention
meets in Chicago.
<p>
Even though some of his lefty followers decry his politics-inspired signing
of welfare reform (after vetoing two similar versions), and even though he
has angered tobacco farmers and industry workers in several states by his
support of tough Food and Drug Administration dictates to the tobacco
industry, he is riding very high.
<p>
Ho-hum! No excitement leading to Nov. 5? Well, it may seem that way --
except for one thing: politics. Funny things happen in politics. Ask Mr.
Bush.
<p>
But for now, President Clinton seems to be master of all he surveys, all
negatives aside. He's smiling with confidence, and not without reason.
Members of Congress who were running away from him two years ago and
dissociating themselves from his administration are now cozying up,
expecting a positive Clinton influence.
<p>
In just a little over two months, we'll know what a majority of voters
think they really want. This week, Mr. Clinton smilingly thinks he knows
the answer already.
<p>
<br>

<i>Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press</i>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
