<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- Clinton, Both Ways On Taxes</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Clinton, Both Ways On Taxes
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Monday, Aug. 19 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
<i>"Probably there are people in this room still mad at me, at that budget,
because you think I raised your taxes too much. It might surprise you to
know that I think I raised them too much, too."</i><br> -- President Bill Clinton,
speaking to a Democratic fund-raiser in Houston, Texas.
<p>
But now that Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole proposes to correct
Mr. Clinton's "raised your taxes too much' mistake, Mr. Clinton is singing
a different song.
<p>
The Dole plan to cut taxes $548 billion over six years, says Mr. Clinton,
is irresponsible and would impose risk upon our economy.
<p>
That was the message of Mr. Clinton in his Saturday radio address. It
followed his Western vacation during the Republican National Convention
that nominated the Bob Dole-Jack Kemp ticket to challenge Mr. Clinton.
<p>
But since Mr. Clinton admits he "raised taxes too much,' why is it wrong
for Sen. Dole to reduce them? Sen. Dole's plan calls for doing away with
unnecessary Cabinet departments and agencies to cut spending, while the
economy is stimulated by the easing of confiscatory taxes to grow faster,
producing more income from lower tax rates applied to a bigger base.
<p>
Over recent decades, we have seen budget deficits continue year after year
-- despite tax increases that we were told were necessary to avoid red ink.
<p>
The trouble is not that the American people have been taxed too little --
but that the federal government has spent too much.
<p>
President George Bush lost re-election to Mr. Clinton in large part because
he went back on his oft-repeated pledge: "Read my lips, no new taxes.' Why
did Mr. Bush abandon that promise? He thought he would cure budget deficits
by raising taxes -- in return for the promise from Democrats in Congress to
cut spending, with the combination of more income and less outgo supposedly
curing the deficit problem.
<p>
But Mr. Bush not only violated his word. He also displayed how politically
naive he was, despite his many years in national politics. He actually
believed the Democrats would cut their spending as they promised. But the
result was a double breaking of faith -- Mr. Bush in raising taxes and the
Democrats in not reducing spending.
<p>
During the 1980s decade, individual income taxes produced 56 percent more
money -- but when that was placed against a 69 percent increase in spending,
the deficits continued.
<p>
Tax increases simply encourage Congress to spend more, allowing government
to grow more. What we need is for Washington to spend less and for the
private economy to grow more.
<p>
That's what the Dole-Kemp ticket proposes.
<p>
But Mr. Clinton, admitting he raised taxes too much, criticized Sen. Dole
for proposing a tax cut -- and simultaneously said he has his own plan for
cutting taxes coming up. Thus the man who admits he raised taxes too much
presumes his tax-cut plan is good -- but the tax-cut plan of his opponent is
all wrong.
<p>
Which one do you trust?
<p>
<br>

Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press
<p>
<br>

