<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- Why Bob Dole?</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Why Bob Dole?
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Friday, Aug. 16 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
His words were simple, blunt and clear. Republican presidential candidate
Bob Dole did not employ flights of rhetoric or fancy phraseology. His
purpose in his presidential nomination acceptance speech at the Republican
National Convention in San Diego last night was simply to show the huge
difference between himself and the presidential alternative, Bill Clinton.
<p>
He did just that.
<p>
Look at Bob Dole's words. Look at his record of action. Look at his dream
for America based on sound moral, family, patriotic, economic,
constitutional values. Then consider the character, the lack of veracity
and integrity, the personality, the record and the promises of the
alternative. In that comparison, it is difficult to understand why Bob Dole
today is the "underdog.' It would seem that principled Americans would be
fleeing from degradation and embracing Sen. Dole's principles to promote
every worthy desire of the American people.
<p>
"Make Or Break'
<p>
Many people said that Sen. Dole's speech last night would be a "make or
break' event. His style was not that of the master Ronald Reagan. He did
not compete with crowd-pleasing Gen. Colin Powell. He did not imitate the
tremendously appealing presentation of Mrs. Elizabeth Dole the night
before. He simply said what needed to be said. He said it plainly, avoiding
fluff and phoniness, addressing the values that have made America great,
but have been so tragically eroded. He spoke for restoration.
<p>
Will we give precedence to the principles Bob Dole champions? Or will we be
caught up in the "sound bite' horse race of presidential elections without
considering the effects? How many will be impressed more by smiles and
platitudes than by hard facts and plain truths? How many will choose prose
over performance? On such things will ride the election of our next
president -- and the future of our nation.
<p>
"After decades of assault upon what made America great, upon supposedly
obsolete values, what have we reaped?' Sen. Dole asked. "What we have in
the opinion of millions of Americans is crime and drugs, illegitimacy,
abortion, the abdication of duty, and the abandonment of children.'
<p>
Our Children
<p>
In a clear challenge to the Clinton administration, with a pointed allusion
to Mrs. Hillary Rodham Clinton's recent book, he asserted: "And after the
virtual devastation of the American family, the rock . . . on which this
country was founded, we are told that it takes a village, that is, the
collective, and thus, the state, to raise a child.
<p>
"The state is now more involved than it has ever been in the raising of
children, and children are now more neglected, abused, and more mistreated
than they have been in our time . . . This is not a coincidence, and, with
all due respect, I am here to tell you, it does not take a village to raise
a child. It takes a family to raise a child . . .
<p>
"I am here to tell you that permissive and destructive behavior must be
opposed, that honor and liberty must be restored, and that individual
accountability must replace collective excuse.'
<p>
Sen. Dole said that "only right conduct' can distinguish our nation.
<p>
"To those who believe that I am too combative, I say, if I am combative, it
is for love of country. It is to uphold a standard that I was born and bred
to defend. And to those who believe that I live and breathe compromise, I
say that in politics, honorable compromise is no sin. It's what protects us
from absolutism and intolerance. But one must never compromise in regard to
God, and family, and honor, and duty and country.'
<p>
Our Economy
<p>
In addition to his appeal for character, personal responsibility and
morality, what does he propose?
<p>
"I do not appreciate the value of economic liberty nearly so much for what
it has done in keeping us fed, as to what it's done in keeping us free . . .
<p>
"And our opponents portray the right to enjoy the fruits of one's own time
and labor as a kind of selfishness against which they must fight for the
good of the nation . . . And now you work from the first of January into
May just to pay your taxes, so that the party of government can satisfy its
priorities with the sweat of your brow, because they think that what you
would do with your own money would be morally and practically less
admirable than what they would do with it.'
<p>
As President
<p>
Sen. Dole said clearly what his election would mean to the American people:
<p>
* "It means you will have a president and a Congress who will have the will
to balance the budget by the year 2002.'
<p>
* "It means you will have a president who will reduce taxes 15 percent
across-the-board for every taxpayer in America. It will include a $500 per
child tax credit for lower- and middle-income families. Taxes for a family
of four making $35,000 would be reduced by more than half -- 56 percent to
be exact. And that's a big, big reduction.'
<p>
* "It means you will have a president who will help small businesses -- the
businesses that create most new jobs -- by reducing the capital gains tax
rate by 50 percent. Cut it in half.'
<p>
* "It means you will have a president who will end the IRS as we know it.'
<p>
* "It means you will have a president who will expand Individual Retirement
Accounts, repeal President Clinton's Social Security tax increase, provide
estate tax relief, reduce government regulation, reform our civil justice
system, provide educational opportunity scholarships, and a host of other
proposals that will create more opportunity, and security for all Americans
and all across America.
<p>
"And I will not stop there. Working with Jack Kemp and a Republican
Congress, I will not be satisfied until we have reformed our entire tax
code, and made it fairer, and flatter and simpler for the American people.'
<p>
* "And given all that I have experienced, I shall always remember those in
need. And that is why I helped save Social Security in 1983. And that is
why I will be the president who preserves, protects and strengthens
Medicare for America's senior citizens.'
<p>
Sen. Dole spoke up for inclusiveness and diversity, for honoring legal
immigrants and defending our borders against invasion by illegal entrants
who drain our taxpayers for social services.
<p>
The Constitution
<p>
In exalting equality for all Americans, Sen. Dole declared: "The
Constitution of the United States mandates equal protection under the law.
This is not code language for racism, it is plain speaking against it.'
<p>
Our Schools
<p>
Sen. Dole understandably lamented the failure of the American education
system which leaves our children's opportunities blighted. He laid much
blame at the feet of the extremely liberal teachers' unions -- not the
teachers.
<p>
"The teachers' unions nominated Bill Clinton in 1992, they are funding his
re-election now, and they, his most reliable supporters, know he will
maintain the status quo,' Sen. Dole said. "And I say this, I say this not
to the teachers, but to their unions, I say this, if education were war,
you would be losing it. If it were a business, you would be driving it into
bankruptcy. If it were a patient, it would be dying . . . I will enrich
your vocabulary with these words you fear -- school choice and competition
and opportunity scholarships -- all this for low and middle income families
so that you will join the rest of us in accountability, while others
compete with you for the commendable privilege of giving our children a
real education.'
<p>
U.S. Command
<p>
He pledged a strong military defense: "And when I am president, every man
and every woman in our Armed Forces will know the president is their
commander in chief -- not Boutros Boutros-Ghali or any other U.N.
secretary-general.'
<p>
He hailed President Reagan: "Were it not for President Reagan, the Soviet
Union would still be standing today.'
<p>
Addressing the drug plague, he said, "We're not the party that, as drug use
has soared among the young, hears no evil, sees no evil, and just cannot
say, "Just say no.' '
<p>
Sen. Dole presented a theme of hope with reality, of morality and strength,
of responsibility and progress, of balanced budgets and governmental
economy with reduced taxation, of better education and less tolerance of
all the evils that attack personal liberty and humanity.
<p>
"I stand before you,' he said, "tested by adversity, made sensitive by
hardship, a fighter by principle and the most optimistic man in America. My
life is proof that America is a land without limits. With my feet on the
ground, and my heart filled with hope, I put my faith in you and in the God
Who loves us all. For I am convinced that America's best days are yet to
come.'
<p>
Contrast
<p>
Do you see the sharp contrast between all of this, proved by many years of
character and service, and the irresponsibility, lack of integrity, high
taxes and enveloping government exemplified by President Clinton?
<p>
This is a time to put aside emotion and to exercise sound judgment, based
on strong moral family values, to lift our nation and our people to the
greatest heights we can achieve.
<p>
Why Bob Dole? He is giving us a choice -- a clear choice. Now it's up to us
all.
<p>
<br>
<br>

Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
