<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- When Conventions Worked</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
When Conventions Worked
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Wednesday, Aug. 14 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
If everyone had known in advance who would win each of the 1996 Olympic
events in Atlanta, it would have been difficult to maintain intense world
attention with just colorful pageantry. But the Republican National
Convention this week and the Democratic National Convention yet to come are
straining hard to be interesting although the presidential nominations of
both were foregone conclusions.
<p>
Once upon a time, political conventions served very important purposes --
and were full of suspense. In fact, they were established to provide
"democracy' in picking our presidential candidates.
<p>
In earlier days in our country, party leaders decided in "smoke-filled
rooms' who the candidates would be. But to get away from "boss' politics,
it was decided that delegates would be elected at the grassroots
state-party level, and they would come together to make the presidential
nominations.
<p>
That was before there were many party primary elections that bound the
delegates to whatever candidate the voters preferred. The delegates, for
the most part, were free agents. Who the nominee would be usually was not
known until several convention ballots thinned the candidate field.
<p>
One of the last big contests was at the 1952 Republican National Convention
in Chicago. "I like Ike' resounded in the Stockyards as war-winning Gen.
Dwight D. Eisenhower was welcomed to national politics. But crusty Sen.
Robert A. Taft, previously a bridesmaid but never the bride, was favored by
more-conservative Republicans.
<p>
In high drama, mellifluous orator Sen. Everett Dirksen took the podium to
look down and condemn the more-liberal, pro-Ike wing of the party, that had
nominated Gov. Tom Dewey in 1948, only to have him defeated by President
Harry Truman. Pointing down at Gov. Dewey, the senator charged, " . . . you
took us down the road to defeat.'
<p>
With Sen. Taft's forces appearing about to fall short, however, there was a
secret plan for him to withdraw dramatically -- then place the name of Gen.
Douglas MacArthur in nomination! Gen. MacArthur demurred, noting that Sen.
Taft had worked so long and so hard. It was agreed to let Sen. Taft stay in
for the first ballot, with the MacArthur switch possible for the second
ballot.
<p>
Such was the suspense, with no sure outcome. But then on the first ballot,
Ike managed a majority, and went on to victory.
<p>
In the Republican National Convention four years earlier, there was even
greater doubt about the winner till the last minute. Four major candidates
were in the contest -- Tom Dewey, Bob Taft, Earl Warren and Harold Stassen.
They courted delegates assiduously all week long in Philadelphia before
Gov. Dewey came out on top, seemingly headed for easy election.
<p>
The Democrats were stuck with President Harry Truman, who then seemed a
"sure loser.' He was unpopular, controversial, and not up to the stature of
President Franklin D. Roosevelt, whose death had put Mr. Truman in the
White House.
<p>
Southern Democrats were angry about Mr. Truman and civil-rights force. So
some created the States Rights Democratic Party, nominating South Carolina
Gov. Strom Thurmond (yes, the venerable Republican of today who then was a
Democrat) for president and Mississippi Gov. Fielding Wright for vice
president, taking votes away from Mr. Truman.
<p>
But fiery Mr. Truman went on the stump, running against the Republican
Congress. He twisted Mr. Dewey's then unfashionable moustache and gained a
surprise victory.
<p>
Ah, those were the days when political conventions were exciting.
<p>
There was, however, significant convention excitement over the Democratic
vice-presidential nominee in 1956 -- particularly concerning Tennessee.
While it is traditional for the presidential nominee to hand-pick his
running mate, Adlai Stevenson, who had a hard time being certain about
anything, couldn't decide on his candidate for vice president. So he threw
the decision to the convention! Surprisingly, Tennessee provided two of the
three major candidates.
<p>
There were Sen. Estes Kefauver and Sen. Albert Gore Sr., father of the
current vice president. The third was young Massachusetts Sen. John F.
Kennedy. Sen. Kefauver outmaneuvered the others and won. Sen. Kennedy thus
avoided being stained by an election defeat -- and came back to be nominated
and elected president four years later.
<p>
In more recent years, primary elections in many states have bound delegates
to the presidential candidates who won state popular votes, meaning the
nomination decisions are known before the conventions are gaveled into
session.
<p>
That's the way it is this year. So Bob Dole and Bill Clinton are having to
depend upon showmanship and pageantry instead of suspense as they accept
the prearranged nominations of their respective conventions.
<p>
The days when conventions were important are long gone. That makes some
wonder whether political conventions will soon go the way of the dinosaurs.
<p>
<br>
<br>

Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press
<p>
<br>

