Last-modified: Tuesday, 13-Aug-96 19:37:10 GMT
Content-length: 9984
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<body>
<title>Lee Anderson -- What Congress, Clinton Did</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
What Congress, Clinton Did
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Monday, Aug. 12 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>

Democratic President Bill Clinton lost his Democratic majority in Congress
two years ago. Conservative Republican majorities were elected in both the
Senate and House of Representatives.
<p>
Well, how has it worked out?
<p>
The answer to that question really should tell the American people whether
Bill Clinton or Bob Dole should be elected president this year -- and
whether the conservative majorities in Congress should be strengthened or
weakened.
<p>
Ticking off short-hand descriptions of action on major governmental issues
is a little boring to read -- but looking at these things can be very, very
informative.
<p>
We urge readers to steel themselves and take time to look.
<p>
Quickly, Congress passed the Congressional Accountability Act, making
Congress subject to the same laws it passes on everyone else.
<p>
It cut spending by Congress on Congress by 10 percent, reducing staffing.
<p>
It stopped "unfunded mandates" on states and others.
<p>
It reformed lobbying laws.
<p>
It put a strict gift-ban on Congress.
<p>
It reformed habeas corpus abuse to make the death penalty for criminals
more effective.
<p>
It sought truthful sentencing to crack down on repeaters.
<p>
It increased prison construction.
<p>
It hit child pornographers.
<p>
It increased money for border patrols against massive illegal immigration.
Mr. Clinton had tried to cut the funding.
<p>
It toughened guidelines on cocaine crimes.
<p>
It raised the earnings limit for Social Security recipients from $12,500 to
$30,000 to allow elders to keep more of the rewards for their work.
<p>
It voted to curb frivolous securities lawsuits -- which Mr. Clinton vetoed --
and then Congress overrode his veto.
<p>
It deregulated much in farming and began subsidy reductions while
increasing environmental protections.
<p>
It reformed telecommunications laws.
<p>
It voted welfare reform -- twice. Mr. Clinton vetoed -- twice. It passed
welfare reform a third time -- getting Mr. Clinton's grudging acceptance as
he was finally forced to act on his campaign promise to "end welfare as we
know it.'
<p>
It passed health-care reform to protect workers from losing insurance
coverage by changing jobs, even for pre-existing conditions.
<p>
It sought to limit government regulations by requiring they be based on
science-and-risk assessments, not just bureaucratic whims. But the effort
was defeated because Democrats thwarted Republican attempts to get the 60
votes needed (they got 59) to end debate and bring the issue to a vote.
<p>
It sought medical malpractice reforms to cut health-care costs -- but again
was stopped short of being able to end debate to get a vote.
<p>
It sought to impose congressional term limits -- with 85 percent of
Republicans voting for limits and 82 percent of Democrats voting against
limits. But a Democratic filibuster prevailed when there were not 60 votes
to stop continuing talk.
<p>
It passed the first balanced budget in 26 years -- but Mr. Clinton vetoed
it!
<p>
It voted to cut foreign aid by 20 percent -- but Mr. Clinton vetoed the
cuts!
<p>
It voted to limit putting U.S. military men and women under U.N. command --
but Mr. Clinton vetoed it!
<p>
It voted tax cuts for 29 million working families in the form of a $500
per-child tax credit -- but Mr. Clinton vetoed it!
<p>
It voted estate-tax reform to help maintain family farms and small family
businesses -- but Mr. Clinton vetoed it!
<p>
It voted to reduce the penalty that costs married couples more when they
file tax returns jointly -- but Mr. Clinton vetoed it!
<p>
It voted to let spouses who work at home invest in IRAs for retirement with
the same benefits as those who work outside the home -- but Mr. Clinton
vetoed it!
<p>
It voted to limit product-liability threats that hinder businesses,
especially small ones, and run up costs -- but Mr. Clinton vetoed it!
<p>
It passed the Medicare Preservation Act to keep Medicare solvent for the
next generation, increasing Medicare spending by 7 percent a year, giving
more choices and increasing per-person Medicare benefits from $4,800 a year
in 1995 to more than $7,000 in 2002 -- but Mr. Clinton vetoed it!
<p>
This is the factual record. It should make the issues clear. It should show
the sharp contrast between conservative Republicans in Congress and Mr.
Clinton and his liberal Democratic congressional minority.
<p>
Now, take the personalities of Mr. Clinton and Sen. Dole and the individual
senators and representatives out of it, if you can. Look just at the
issues. Which side do you think stands for what's best for our country and
the American people?
<p>
The people we elect on Nov. 5 will make a great deal of difference -- for
better or for worse -- in our future and that of our country.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
Fast Counting
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>

<p>
The first computer amazed statisticians by making calculations at the rate
of 5,000 numbers a second. But that seems awfully slow nowadays.
<p>
Most desktop personal computers can crunch numbers at the rate of 20
million calculations a second. A supercomputer in Japan holds the current
record of 220 billion calculations a second.
<p>
A new supercomputer being developed by the U.S. Department of Energy at the
Sandia National Laboratories in New Mexico will set a new record. It costs
$46 million, uses enough electricity to run 80-100 homes, and is as big as
a small house.
<p>
This model is expected to deliver 1.8 trillion calculations a second!
<p>
But the sky is still the limit. The Energy Department's "Operation Blue'
will be shooting for 10 trillion calculations a second.
<p>
Others talk of achieving a quadrillion operations a second.
<p>
These are numbers enough to make your head swim.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
A New "Dust Bowl"
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>

<p>


In the film version of The Grapes of Wrath, there's a scene where a
well-fed fellow tells a drought- and debt-ridden Oklahoma farmer that he
and his family will have to leave their land. When the farmer asks him
who's responsible for it all, the guy bites the end off his cigar, spits it
out, and says, "Brother, I don't know. If I did, I'd tell you. I just don't
know who's to blame.'
<p>
The "Okies' were victims of natural and economic forces beyond anyone's
control. They suffered much, but they survived, and their saga has taken
its place in American legend.
<p>
Will there be a new John Steinbeck to immortalize the Americans who are
being forced off their land today -- not by drought or Depression, but by
drug-dealing criminals?
<p>
Texans along the Rio Grande "have begun selling their ranches to the
highest bidders, who happen to be fronting for the very Mexican drug
traffickers who intimidated the ranchers into abandoning their livelihoods
and way of life,' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, during
congressional hearings.
<p>
One rancher fearfully testified wearing a black hood and raincoat, speaking
behind a curtain into a microphone that altered his voice.
<p>
According to Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, many others "were contacted but have
refused to testify for fear of extreme reprisal by Mexican drug cartels.'
<p>
It's infuriating to see such stark evidence of how criminals have gained
the upper hand in our country.
<p>
And who is to blame for it all?
<p>
How about those who softened the law to the point where vicious hoodlums no
longer fear it? How about those who despise the law, promoting illegal drug
use?
<p>
How about President Bill Clinton? His administration has notoriously
tolerated recent illegal drug use by many of its own staffers, ignoring the
fact that the doper's dollar is what puts power into the hands of the drug
cartels.
<p>
Unlike the "Dust Bowl' of the '30s, the drug plague of modern times has
plenty of villains -- some of them in high office.
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<center>
<h3>
Look Who's "Privileged"
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>

<p>


Voters often complain about the special "privileges' that members of
Congress get. Sometimes the complaints are valid. Sometimes they're not.
Sometimes what we see as privileges are designed to facilitate the work of
our senators and representatives.
<p>
But what about congressional privileges used by people who are not members
of Congress?
<p>
Washingtonian magazine reports that the "domestic companions' of three
congressmen who are not married and have identified themselves as
homosexuals are using "official' congressional ID cards that allow them to
park in Capitol Hill garages and go freely in and out of restricted areas
of the Capitol even in times of heightened security.
<p>
Each card says: "This is to certify that the person whose name and
photograph appear on the card is the spouse of the above named member of
the United States House of Representatives.'
<p>
That is a false certification.
<p>
Our law does not recognize "homosexual marriage' or "same-sex marriage.'
And the congressmen involved in this misrepresentation do not have
"spouses.'
<p>
They are Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass.; Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., and Rep.
Steve Gunderson, R-Wis.
<p>
<br>
<br>

Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
