<title>Lee Anderson -- Excitement Over Jack Kemp</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Excitement Over Jack Kemp
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br>Friday, Aug. 9 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>


Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole has promised to name his 
choice for vice president tomorrow. But while speculation has centered 
on outstanding men like Sen. John McCain, Sen. Connie Mack, Gov. John 
Engler and others, there was something less than great excitement. 
<p>
It seemed the Republican National Convention in San Diego next week 
was doomed to fall far below the Olympics in public interest.
<p>
But then the name of Jack Kemp was leaked as a vice-presidential 
possibility. And excitement was generated.
<p>
Mr. Kemp, a former pro football quarterback who made an admirable name 
for himself as a prominent member of the U.S. House of Representatives 
from New York, and then as Housing and Urban Development secretary, 
was almost a presidential candidate himself this year. Lots of 
admirers wish he had been. And now, many would like to see him on Sen. 
Dole's ticket.
<p>
Mr. Kemp didn't run for president, it was reported, for two primary 
reasons. The big one was that he didn't want to fight the necessary 
battle to raise millions of dollars in campaign funds demanded for the 
primary battles. And he was said to feel he might seem a little too 
"moderate' in comparison with the agenda of the admirably conservative 
new Republican majorities in both houses of Congress.
<p>
Then in the 1996 primaries, Mr. Kemp, who had contested Sen. Dole for 
the presidential nomination that neither of them gained in 1988, 
endorsed presidential aspirant Steve Forbes. The main reason was that 
he liked Mr. Forbes' flat-tax, balanced-budget, pro-growth economic 
policies.
<p>
Now, however, Mr. Forbes is prominent among the Dole supporters. And 
Mr. Kemp will soon be if the rumors of his possible selection for the 
vice presidential spot on the Dole ticket prove true tomorrow.
<p>
A Dole-Kemp ticket could probably enliven what up to now has been a 
rather dull campaign. Mr. Kemp is seen as a strong proponent of the 
kind of economic policies needed to provide great progress for our 
people and nation. 
<p>
While no vice presidential candidate is likely to be the decisive 
factor in determining the presidential winner in the contest between 
Sen. Dole and President Bill Clinton, Mr. Kemp undoubtedly would give 
strength to Mr. Dole's campaign.
<p>
Peculiarly, the election of the next president may not be based on 
facts and policies at all. The winner may be picked according to 
personal perceptions that ignore real national issues and questions of 
character. And that is not a compliment to the judgment of American 
voters.
<p>
Mr. Clinton has proved he cannot be trusted to stand anywhere. 
Basically a liberal, he has flip-flopped in accord with what he has 
believed at any moment to be expedient in seeking to gain personal 
advantage. He espouses no firm principles whatsoever. Whatever he has 
said on one occasion, he almost surely has denied on another. His 
personal morality is a negative that seems strangely to be ignored. 
His deserved nickname of "Slick Willie' has been proved over and over 
again. Most Americans are shown by polls to believe he is not honest 
and does not have integrity. And women, usually sensitive to issues of 
morality related to women, seem to have ignored almost completely his 
undisputable record of womanizing. Mr. Clinton's smiling "aw shucks' 
personality seems to have triumphed over all facts and all values and 
all issues to give him a wide margin of preference.
<p>
That's a poor basis on which to choose a president of the United 
States. But "what works' seems to be the key in 1996 presidential 
politics.
<p>
Contrast that with Sen. Dole, a man of character and strong 
conservative principles, and with Mr. Kemp, a man of stability and 
practical views for governmental economic responsibility and 
limitations, and the Clinton-Gore ticket ought to be lost in the dust. 
But politics is strange business.
<p>
All of those mentioned as possible choices by Sen. Dole for vice 
president are outstanding people. But Mr. Kemp probably would bring 
more to the ticket than any of the others.
<p>
So we watch with interest to see what Sen. Dole will announce 
tomorrow.
<p>
<br>
<br>

Copyright 1996, The Chattanooga Free Press
<p>
<br>

