<title>Michelle Malkin -- Educators Are Teaching Their Union A Lesson In Fairness</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
          Educators Are Teaching Their Union A Lesson In Fairness
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>by Michelle Malkin
<br>Seattle Times
<br>August 19, 1996
</i>
<p>
When was the last time you shelled out $600 to support
an organization or cause of your choice?  It's a luxury few
of us can afford -- yet thousands of educators across the
country have been forced to fork over such astronomical
membership dues each year to teachers unions that spend
their money on objectionable political activities.
<p>
Union leaders dismiss this charge as nonsense.  No one's
forced to do anything, they say, and nothing they do is
objectionable.  But don't tell that to teachers in Illinois,
Michigan, and California who have all successfully
challenged the use of their compulsory union dues for
partisan activities.  And don't tell it to the nearly 300 teachers
in this state who are now organizing a lawsuit against the
Washington Education Assocation (WEA) for using "their
hard-earned wages for political causes that have nothing
do with improving education, their salary or benefits."
<p>
A little background:  Two years ago, 121 public school
teachers and other employees in Washington won
a settlement with the WEA to reduce their dues by over
50 percent.  That settlement expired in June, and now the
group is preparing to sue if the WEA refuses to reach a
similar agreement out of court.  Seattle attorney Steven
 O'Ban of Ellis, Li and McKinstry, who is representing
the maverick teachers, notes: "A lot of teachers don't
know they have the right not to be forced to pay for
political activities they don't believe in.  We're in the
process of getting the word out so teachers know."
(School employees interested in joining the effort should
contact Kristy Bergland by August 31 at (509) 326-7500.)
<p>
The dissenting educators are [ital]not[ital] anti-union.
They simply believe their dues should be spent on
essential union services -- and nothing more.  As Cindy Omlin,
a speech-language pathologist for the Spokane School District, explained to me, "Teachers (who pay between $400 and
 $600 in annual union fees) feel like they're being exploited
for their money."
<p>
Carolyn Jacobs, a teacher in the Mead School District,
adds that: "Teachers joined this challenge for a
variety of reasons.  Some joined because they say their
money is funding political ideologies that violate
their personal convictions while others opposed the
funding of candidate endorsements.  All want the
union to be a more effective advocate for them as teachers."
<p>
For Barbara Amidon, who teaches in western Washington,
 joining the WEA challenge "was an incredibly difficult
decision.  But it was a matter of principle and integrity,
fairness and free speech."  Together, she and her husband
(also a teacher) were paying nearly $1,200 in local, state
and national union dues.  As political literature from both the
WEA and the National Education Association (NEA)
came pouring into her mailbox during election cycles,
Amidon became curious about how and where her
dues were being spent.
<p>
State union leaders refused to provide that information
unless Amidon gave up her membership.  She and
her husband did so reluctantly.  "I am absolutely not anti-union,"
Amidon says.  "I would just like them to
let us know how they're spending our money."
<p>
Here's a hint: Next week, the NEA will send more delegates
the Democratic National Convention in
Chicago than any other organization or state.  In 1992, the
National Education Association loaned
one-fifth of its top brass to the Clinton-Gore campaign in the
final two weeks of the election. During the
1993-1994 election cycle, the NEA gave $ 2.2 million to
Democrats (and just $25,800 to Republicans),
according to Federal Election Commission figures.
 In addition, the union spends more than $39 million
annually on field organization.  And at its annual convention,
the NEA has passed resolutions on such
fundamental education issues as human rights in Nigeria and
a boycott of Florida orange juice because
the industry employed talk show host Rush Limbaugh as
a spokesman.
<p>
Jeff Leer, a physical education teacher in the Sedro-Woolley
school district who once served as a union
building representative, told me he is saddened that the
unions have "strayed far from their original intent
of improving working conditions and engaging in collective
bargaining."  He knows conservative and liberal teachers
alike who are "deeply offended" by the union's partisan
activism.  Like Barbara Amidon, it was the overflow of
political literature from the WEA that pushed him over
the edge and convinced him to resign: "That was
really demeaning.  They were using my money to tell me how
to vote."
<p>
Ultimately, the dissenters agree, their challenge isn't
about dollars. As the Austrian economist Friedrich
Hayek wrote, "The coercion which unions have been
permitted to exercise, contrary to all principles of
freedom under the law, is primarily the coercion of fellow
workers."  This is a challenge aimed at preserving liberty
and fairness.  It is a warning to public-sector unions that force
against its members will not be tolerated.  And it is a
lesson in political courage from which all students of democracy
can learn.
<p>
 -- <a href="mailto:malkin1@ix.netcom.com">Michelle Malkin</a>
<p>
<br>
<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
