<body>
<title>Michelle Malkin -- New Americans Strengthen the Bonds of Citizsenship</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
             New Americans Strengthen the Bonds of Citizenship
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>by Michelle Malkin
<br>Seattle Times
<br>June 30, 1996
</i>
<p>
Pop quiz:  What are the basic duties of Congress?
How does the impeachment process work? Why
do we have a holiday on the Fourth of July?
<p>
Visit your nearest community college, church, or
adult education center, and you will find diligent
immigrants across the country boning up on these
basics in preparation for the U.S. citizenship exam.
Next week, thousands of fortunate students who
have aced the intensive testing process -- including
some 500 immigrants here in Seattle -- will stand
before a judge on the most patriotic day of the
year and take an oath of citizenship, which reads
in part:
<p>
<blockquote>
<i>"I hereby declare on oath that I absolutely
and entirely renounce and abjure all allegiance
and fidelity to any foreign prince, potentate, state
or sovereignty of whom or which I have heretofore
been a subject or citizen; that I will support and
defend the Constitution and laws of the United
States of America against all enemies, foreign
and domestic; that I will bear true faith and
allegiance to the same...so help me God." </i>
</blockquote>
<p>
Anyone who has ever attended or participated
in a citizenship ceremony cannot read these words
without awe and remembrance.  The oath-taking
by new Americans, especially on Independence
Day, is one of the most overwhelming and
unifying experiences in civic life.  It is one of the
few public events left -- with the possible exception
of the Olympics -- where raw patriotism can be
unleashed without fear of retribution from the cynical
or politically correct.
<p>
In an era in which the public schools now celebrate
Cinco de Mayo, Chinese New Year and Black
History Month more fervently than Flag Day,
Memorial Day and President's Day, the common
ritual of naturalization helps to preserve the "United"
in the United States of America.
<p>
You will not hear half-mumbled Pledges of Allegiances
at the citizenship ceremony.  Nor will attendees cackle,
like they do at most major sports events, when the
soloist strains to ask "O, say does that Star-Spangled
Baaanner yet waave?"  The new Americans will all be
too busy belting it out the line themselves.  This is
from-the-lungs patriotism that seems sadly to be
disappearing from much of civic life.
<p>
Just take a look at what has happened to another
once-unified rite of passage -- college graduations.
At UCLA, the University of Pennsylvania, and
Vassar College, to name just a few, separate
commencement ceremonies for minority students
are now held.  Many graduates also depart with
separate ethnic and racial yearbooks, the better to
hold all their fine memories of self-segregated life
on campus.  With so many foreigners literally dying
to be Americans -- the Chinese in boats, the
Mexicans by foot -- it's appalling how many
young, hyphenated Americans (Asian-Americans,
Latino-Americans, African-Americans) seem so
intent on devaluing their citizenship.
<p>
Becoming a naturalized American isn't easy, not
least of all because it requires applicants to endure
the torturous INS bureaucracy. (Just try calling
your local office, stopwatch in hand, and see
how long it takes to reach a live voice.  You might
also want to pack a light snack and pillow.)
Immigrants must be legal residents in the U.S. for
at least five years before they can apply for citizenship.
They must pass an FBI criminal background check.
Then pass an oral interview with an INS officer to
demonstrate English proficiency.  And then pass a
knowledge test on U.S. history and government.
<p>
Two years ago, the INS and several community
colleges in Seattle, Olympia and Yakima launched
a one-of-a-kind pilot program to expedite the
naturalization process.  Participants enroll in a
rigorous, 10-week course on American history and
government. At the end of the session, they can
take the test -- bypassing the INS's routine delays.
The only requirement is that students be proficient
in English prior to enrollment.
<p>
Nahid Eng, a naturalized American citizen who
emigrated from Iran in 1974, taught her first 10-week
session this spring at Bellevue Community College.
Her students, who ranged in age from 29 to 77
years old, came from all over the world:  Korea,
Taiwan, India, Sri Lanka, Czechoslovakia, Poland,
Singapore, Holland, Germany, Canada and the
United Kingdom. E Pluribus Unum in living color.
<p>
She drew on an exhaustive variety of sources,
from the INS to the Daughters of the American
Revolution, to prepare her students for their
upcoming July 2 exam. They surveyed American
history from the Civil War to the Vietnam War; and
pored over the Declaration of Independence,
Constitution, and Bill of Rights.  They memorized
the Pledge of Allegiance.  "I gave them a crash
course in what it takes to be an American," Eng said.
<p>
How many native-born high school graduates,
I wonder, have read the Bill of Rights in its entirety?
How many  schools still begin their day with the
Pledge of Allegiance?   It wouldn't be a bad idea
to require native-born Americans, like those who
seek naturalization, to demonstrate proficiency in civics.
Or at least to be familiar with the process by which
immigrants join them as new Americans.
<p>
 -- <a href="mailto:malkin1@ix.netcom.com">Michelle Malkin</a>
<p>
<br>
<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
</html>
