<HEAD><title>Subsidies Cost
 -- ATR</title></HEAD>
<BODY Bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER>
<BOLD><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>
Subsidies Cost
</FONT></center></bold><HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=30%>


	ATR recently issued a list of corporate welfare spending programs and government subsidies that should be the first things on the chopping block when Congress pares down the budget.  Leading the list were a number of outdated energy programs that serve few people, yet cost us all dearly.   Direct and indirect subsidies to government-owned utilities alone cost American consumers billions of dollars annually.  ATR supports the elimination of the Department of Energy, privatization of the Power Marketing Administrations, and the elimination of the Rural Utilities Service.<P>
	ATR President Grover Norquist recently said, "We need to get government out of trying to run businesses.  Just look at the mess the government has made of the electric utility industry.  Directand indirect subsidies are taking close to $10 billion out of taxpayers' pockets annually and throwing them at government-owned electric utilities who also receive tax breaks.  At a time when all Americans have been forced to tighten their belts and Congress has to make tough decisions about the new budget, it is absurd to even consider continuing these wasteful spending programs.<P>
	"One of the things the government of Poland learned is that privately-run companies don't need subsidies and bailouts.  Bill Clinton's energy policies should learn from the failures in Eastern Europe, not emulate them.  It's time to privatize and get the government out of the energy business.  The government simply does not need to be in the electric utility industry -- either directly, through subsidies, or through special tax breaks.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><a href="/atr/bar.map"><img src="/atr/bar.gif" ismap border="0"></a> </CENTER>
 <P> 
