<HEAD><title>Reporters Notebook -- ATR</title></HEAD>
<BODY Bgcolor=#FFFFFF><CENTER><a href="/atr/bar4.map"><img src="/atr/bar4.gif" ismap border="0"></a>  </CENTER>
<BOLD><CENTER><FONT SIZE=+3>Wall Street Meets Grover</FONT></CENTER></BOLD>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="reptnote.gif"><P>

	One of the most widely read political columns in America is "Potomac Watch" by Paul A. Gigot in The Wall Street Journal.  When he isn't sparring with analyst Mark Shields on <ADDRESS>The McNeil/Lehrer News Hour,</ADDRESS> Gigot is spotting new trends and personalities.  Gigot's April 14 "Potomac Watch" column described the impact that ATR and ATR President Grover Norquist are having on Washington's agenda.<P>
  	Calling Norquist the "V.I. Lenin of the anti-tax movement," Gigot explains that while once candidates for president courted the endorsement of other major office holders, now they seek support from groups like ATR that emphasize communications with local cadres.  Gigot points out that Grover is a key organizer of meetings of many groups in what he calls the "Leave UsAlone" coalition that resists excessive federal intervention in American life.<P>
	"Real political clout rests with issue-driven activists who can mobilize grassroots networks."  Enter Mr. Network, Grover Norquist.<P>
 	"Mr. Norquist founded his group, Americans for Tax Reform, in 1985, and he now communicates with 1,800 state and local tax outfits."  Gigot point outs that Grover is a key organizer of meetings of many groups in what he calls the "Leave Us Alone" coalition that resists excessive federal intervention in American life.<P>
	"Mr. Norquist is the Grand Central Station of this coalition," writes Gigot.  He also points out that just before Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole (R-Kan.) announced for president, he started off his campaign by joining Grover Norquist for a photograph to sign the ATR Taxpayer Protection Pledge.<P>
	Well there you have it.  Gigot metaphors describe the ATR president as a deceased Bolshevik, a New York train station, and the bosses of Tammany Hall.  Not a bad combination.<P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>British Cousins Take Notice</FONT>
<P>


	The Economist is Britain's widely respected contribution to readers of international finance and political trends.  The magazine's "American Survey" department for the April 15-21 issue took note of a new book by ATRF President Grover Norquist called <ADDRESS>Rock the House.</ADDRESS> Comparing the Norquist world view with that of President Clinton's pollster Stanley Greenberg in another new book, a correspondent for The Economist writes:  "Mr. Norquist thinks Mr. Greenberg is in denial.  It is not the party order that is collapsing, it is the Democratic Party.  Meanwhile, the Republican coalition, as he calls it, is going from strength to strength."<P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Cent Jours.  Et Apres?</FONT>
<P>


	Reporters in France also followed the first 100 days of the new Congress and ATR's impact on the congressional agenda.  On page 36 of  his cover story for the May issue of <ADDRESS>Le temps de l'Eglise</ADDRESS> (Church Times),  the international Catholic magazine published in Paris, reporter Daniel Rabourdin examines the hundred days and after.  The article offers a capsule description of ATR membership and  programs and takes particular note of  how the Taxpayer Protection Pledge is changing Congress.<P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Moving and Shaking</FONT>
<P>


	The ultimate political trade publication in Washington is a slick magazine called Campaigns and Elections.  The May issue devotes one page to ATR's own fuzzy curmudgeon, describing Grover Norquist as one of the town's "Movers and Shakers."  The magazine asked Grover what he would do if he were president (of the country  that is - not just ATR) for one day.  Grover's reply:  "I would fire everybody in government and quit.  Then lock the doors to the White House and Congress, so no one could get back in."  Who says hyperbole can't make a legitimate and humorous point.  That is, if it was hyperbole.<P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Even Gentleman's Quarterly?
</FONT>
<P>
	GQ may not be the first publication that comes to mind when one thinks about news coverage of public policy makers.  But lo and behold, there in the May issue with Mel Gibson on the cover is an earnest looking ATR President Grover Norquist looking out at readers from an article by John B. Judis titled "Newt's Gang."  Grover is flanked by a rogues' gallery of conservative policy strategists such as Heritage Foundation President Edwin Feulner, <ADDRESS>American Spectator</ADDRESS> publisher Emmet Tyrrell, and the CATO Institute President Ed Crane.  The subtitle of the article is "Meet the Real Establishment."  This group was not chosen for its snappy sartorial ensembles. That's why cinema heartthrob Mel Gibson is still on the cover.<P>

  <HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Boston Globe and Points South

</FONT>
<P>
	Articles by ATRF President Grover Norquist were printed recently in the <ADDRESS>Boston Globe</ADDRESS> and <ADDRESS>The Washington Times</ADDRESS> examining  the first 100 days.  Norquist's conclusion: Bring on the next 500 days.<P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>TV COVERS DAY OF OUTRAGE </FONT>
<P>

	ATR members and friends focused national TV attention on the burden of federal taxation on Saturday, April 15, during a rally across the street from the White House in LaFayette Park.  Speakers included Grover Norquist, President of Americans for Tax Reform (ATR) and the Americans for Tax Reform Foundation (ATRF), Amy Moritz, President of The National Center for Policy Research; Dr. Marlo Lewis, Jr., Executive Director of the Competitive Enterprise Institute; Fran Smith, Executive Director of Consumer Alert; Jeffrey Pierce, Regulatory Analyst for Citizens for a Sound Economy; Peter Ferrara, Senior Fellow for the National Center for Policy Analysis; and Wes Anderson, former Executive Director of Frontiers of Freedom.<P>
	"This protest is for millions of taxpayers who are angry about high taxes, pork-barrel spending, and the growth of the federal bureaucracy," said Norquist.  The Washington, D.C., rally was one of several at sites around the country organized by taxpayer groups under the banner of "Day of Outrage."  Both CBS and CNN ran network stories that night.  More than 60 major net-work-affiliated TV stations as well as independents in major markets ran stories about the rally.<P>
	"We will be protesting, as our forefathers did in Boston Harbor, that runaway tax and spend government policies must stop now," Norquist said.<P>
	Dozens of protestors signalled their approval of remarks by blowing on plastic duck calls with a "no new taxes" slogan printed on each one.<P>
  	Both CBS and CNN ran network stories that night. More than 60 major network-affiliated TV stations as well as independents in major markets ran stories about the rally.  This level of coverage shows that ATR is taken seriously by major media.  Here is a partial list of broadcast reports in major cities which covered this significant ATR rally reaching tens of millions of viewers.  Broadcast times and content are confirmed by an independent report from Video Monitoring Services of America, Inc. for April 15, 1995.<P>
