Flat Tax Alternative</FONT>
	Thank you for your prompt response to my request for information on the "flat tax" proposals.  It will help me answer and ask appropriate questions when dealing with neighbors, our local candidates, and radio talk show hosts.<P>
	Two reasons for my interest are:<P>
	1.  I am an American citizen paying taxes to a government which doesn't have a responsible attitude toward spending.<P>
	2.  I plan on starting a small home-based business and even though I am a bookkeeper, the tax laws are presently so confusing that I dread even thinking about April 15, 1996.<P>
	Your ideas are responsible and simplified.  I have contact with many people who would like to receive your "taxpayer action alerts."<P>

Penelope Knight
Karlstad, Minnesota

Editor's note:  Since this is the first issue of American Tax Reformer, we are printing here a few letters recently sent to staff in the Washington, D.C., office of Americans for Tax Reform.<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=2 WIDTH=40%>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Reduce Super Waste</FONT>
<P>
	I have just finished Martin Gross's book "A Call for Revolution" and have run across your organization in a list in the appendix.<P>
	I was one of the citizens convinced of Washington's inefficiencies and excesses long before I read Mr. Gross's book, but I am now inspired to advocate the idea of practical steps towards rationalization and reduction of the super wasteful spending of our seemingly irresponsible governments.  I would welcome and hope to participate in the advocacy of every suggestion Mr. Gross makes, and hope that your organization may provide a channel for that endeavor.  Please be so kind as to send me whatever information you disseminate about your organization and a list of activities.  I would also like a history of your efforts if  you have one or a list of publications which can educate me concerning your public record.<P>

Rockwell R. Blake
Plattsburgh, New York


